# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: château-des-baux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The **ballista** (Latin, from Greek βαλλίστρα *ballistra* and that from βάλλω *ballō*, "throw"), plural **ballistae** or **ballistas**, sometimes called **bolt thrower**, was an ancient projectile weapon that launched either bolts or stones at a distant target.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Developed from earlier Greek weapons, it relied upon different mechanics, using two levers with torsion springs instead of a tension prod (the bow part of a modern crossbow).
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The springs consisted of several loops of twisted skeins.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Early versions projected heavy darts or spherical stone projectiles of various sizes for siege warfare.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It developed into a smaller precision weapon, the *scorpio*, and possibly the *polybolos*.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The early ballistae in Ancient Greece were developed from two weapons called oxybeles and gastraphetes.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The gastraphetes ('belly-bow') was a handheld crossbow.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It had a composite prod and was spanned by bracing the front end of the weapon against the ground while placing the end of a slider mechanism against the stomach.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The operator would then walk forward to arm the weapon while a ratchet prevented it from shooting during loading.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] This produced a weapon that, it was claimed, could be operated by a person of average strength but which had a power that allowed it to be used against armored troops.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The oxybeles were a bigger and heavier construction employing a winch and were mounted on a tripod.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It had a lower rate of fire and was used as a siege engine.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] With the invention of the torsion spring bundle, the first ballistae could now be built.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The advantage of this new technology was the fast relaxation time of this system.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Thus it was possible to shoot lighter projectiles with higher velocities over a longer distance.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] By contrast, the comparatively slow relaxation time of the bow or prod of a conventional crossbow such as the oxybeles meant that much less energy could be transferred to light projectiles, limiting the effective range of the weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The earliest form of the ballista is thought to have been developed for Dionysius of Syracuse, c.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] All components that were not made of wood were transported in the baggage train.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It would be assembled with local wood, if necessary.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Some were positioned inside large, armored, mobile siege towers or even on the edge of a battlefield.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] For all of the tactical advantages offered, it was only under Philip II of Macedon, and even more so under his son Alexander, that the ballista began to develop and gain recognition as both a siege engine and field artillery.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Historical accounts, for instance, cited that Philip II employed a group of engineers within his army to design and build catapults for his military campaigns.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] There is even a claim that it was Philip II with his team of engineers who invented the ballista after improving Dionysius's device, which was merely an oversized slingshot.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It was further perfected by Alexander, whose own team of engineers introduced innovations such as the idea of using springs made from tightly strung coils of rope instead of a bow to achieve more energy and power when throwing projectiles.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Polybius reported about the usage of smaller, more portable ballistae, called scorpions, during the Second Punic War.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Ballistae could be easily modified to shoot both spherical and shaft projectiles, allowing their crews to adapt quickly to prevailing battlefield situations in real time.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] After the absorption of the Ancient Greek city-states into the Roman Republic in 146 BC, the highly advanced Greek technology began to spread across many areas of Roman influence.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] This included the great military machine advances the Greeks had made (most notably by Dionysus of Syracuse), as well as all the scientific, mathematical, political and artistic developments.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The Romans adopted the torsion-powered ballista, which had by now spread to several cities around the Mediterranean, all of which became Roman spoils of war, including one from Pergamon, which was depicted among a pile of trophy weapons in relief on a balustrade.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The torsion ballista, developed by Alexander, was a far more complicated weapon than its predecessor and the Romans developed it even further, especially into much smaller versions, that could be easily carried.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The early Roman *ballistae* were made of wood and metal, and held together with iron plates around the frames and iron nails in the stand.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The main stand had a slider on the top, into which were loaded the bolts or stone *shot*.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Attached to this, at the back, was a pair of 'winches' and a 'claw', used to ratchet the bowstring back to the armed firing position.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The slider passed through the *field frames* of the weapon, in which were located the *torsion springs* (rope made of animal sinew), which were twisted around the bow arms, which in turn, were attached to the bowstring.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Drawing the bowstring back with the winches twisted the already taut springs, storing the energy to fire the projectiles.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The bronze or iron caps, which secured the torsion bundles were adjustable by means of pins and peripheral holes, which allowed the weapon to be tuned for symmetrical power and for changing weather conditions.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The *ballista* was a highly accurate weapon (there are many accounts of single soldiers being picked off by ballistarii), but some design aspects meant it could compromise its accuracy for range.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The maximum range was over 500 yards (460 m), but the effective combat range for many targets was far shorter.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The Romans continued the development of the *ballista*, and it became a highly prized and valued weapon in the army of the Roman Empire.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It was used, just before the start of the Empire, by Julius Caesar during his conquest of Gaul and on both of his campaigns in subduing Britain.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The first of Caesar's invasions of Britain took place in 55 BC, after a rapid and successful initial conquest of Gaul, in part as an expedition, and more practical to try to put an end to the reinforcements sent by the native Britons to fight the Romans in Gaul.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] A total of eighty means of transport, carrying two legions, attempted to land on the British shore, only to be driven back by the many British warriors assembled along the shoreline.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The ships had to unload their troops on the beach, as it was the only one suitable for many miles, yet the massed ranks of British charioteers and javeliners were making it difficult.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] In Gaul, the stronghold of Alesia was under a Roman siege in 52 BC, and was completely surrounded by a Roman fortification including a wooden palisade and towers.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] As was standard siege technique at the time, small *ballistae* were placed in the towers with other troops armed with bows or slings.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The use of the *ballista* in the Roman siege strategy was also demonstrated in the case of the Siege of Masada.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] During the conquest of the Empire, the ballista proved its worth many times in sieges and battles, both at sea and on land.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It is from the time of the Roman Empire that many of the archaeological finds of ballistae date.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Accounts by the finders, including technical manuals and journals, are used today by archaeologists to reconstruct these weapons.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] After Julius Caesar, the ballista was a permanent fixture in the Roman army and, over time, modifications and improvements were made by successive engineers.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] This included replacing the remaining wooden parts of the machine with metal, creating a much smaller, lighter and more powerful machine than the wooden version, which required less maintenance (though the vital torsion springs were still vulnerable to the strain).
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The largest ballistae of the 4th century could throw a dart further than 1200 yards (1,100 m).
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The carroballista was a cart-mounted version of the weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] There were probably different models of ballista under the *cheiroballistra* class, at least two different two-wheeled models and one model with four wheels.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Their probable size was roughly 1.47 m (4 ft 10 in) width, i.e., 5 Roman feet.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The cart system and structure gave it a great deal of flexibility and capability as a battlefield weapon, since the increased maneuverability allowed it to be moved with the flow of the battle.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] This weapon features several times on Trajan's Column.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It has been speculated that the Roman military may have also fielded a 'repeating' ballista, also known as a *polybolos*.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Reconstruction and trials of such a weapon carried out in a BBC documentary, *What the Romans Did For Us*, showed that they "were able to shoot eleven bolts a minute, which is almost four times the rate at which an ordinary ballista can be operated".
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] However, no example of such a weapon has been found by archaeologists.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The cheiroballistra and the manuballista are held by many scholars to be the same weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The difference in name may be attributable to the different languages spoken in the Empire.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Latin remained the official language in the Western Empire, but the Eastern Empire predominantly used Greek, which added an extra 'r' to the word ballista.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The manuballista was a handheld version of the traditional ballista.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] This new version was made entirely of iron, which conferred greater power to the weapon, since it was smaller, and less iron (an expensive material before the 19th century), was used in its production.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It was not the ancient gastraphetes, but the Roman weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] However, the same physical limitations applied as with the gastraphetes.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Archaeology, and in particular experimental archaeology, has been influential on this subject.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Although several ancient authors (such as Vegetius) wrote very detailed technical treatises, providing us with all the information necessary to reconstruct the weapons, all their measurements were in their native language and therefore highly difficult to translate.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] Attempts to reconstruct these ancient weapons began at the end of the 19th century, based on rough translations of ancient authors.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] It was only during the 20th century, however, that many of the reconstructions began to make any sense as a weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] By bringing in modern engineers, progress was made with the ancient systems of measurement.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] By redesigning the reconstructions using the new information, archaeologists in that specialty were able to recognise certain finds from Roman military sites, and identify them as ballistae.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The information gained from the excavations was fed into the next generation of reconstructions and so on.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The most influential archaeologists in this area have been Peter Connolly and Eric Marsden, who have not only written extensively on the subject but have also made many reconstructions themselves and have refined the designs over many years of work.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] With the decline of the Roman Empire, resources to build and maintain these complex machines became very scarce, so the ballista was likely supplanted initially by the simpler and cheaper onager and the more efficient springald.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] The Littere Wallie records the existence of 4 "balistas ad turrimi" at "Duluithelan" [Dolwyddelan] Castle in 1280, one "balistam de tur" at "Rothelano"[Rhuddlan] castle and one "magnam ballistam" at "Bere Blada" Castle [Castell y Bere?] in 1286.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] These all being held under the authority of the English Crown.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] In more remote regions such as Ireland, where cannons were rare and personal firearms were almost non-existent, ballistae had recorded use well into late 15th century.
[src:château-des-baux/ballista] While not a direct descendant mechanically, the concept and naming continues on as arbalest crossbows (*arcus* 'bow' + ballista).
[src:château-des-baux/base-mérimée] The ***Base Mérimée*** (French pronunciation: [baz meʁime]) is the database of French monumental and architectural heritage, created and maintained by the French Ministry of Culture.
[src:château-des-baux/base-mérimée] It was created in 1978, and placed online in 1995.
[src:château-des-baux/base-mérimée] The database is periodically updated, and contains more than 320,000 entries as of October 2020.
[src:château-des-baux/base-mérimée] It covers religious, domestic, agricultural, educational, military and industrial architecture, and is subdivided into three domains: historical monuments, general inventory, and architecture (including remarkable contemporary architecture).
[src:château-des-baux/base-mérimée] The database was named after writer, historian and inspector-general of historical monuments Prosper Mérimée, who published the first survey of historic monuments in 1840.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Marseille, France's second-largest city, has one of the largest container ports in the country.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] It prides itself on being France's oldest city, founded by Greek settlers from Phocaea around 600 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Bouches-du-Rhône is the most populous department of the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region and the third most populous of France, with 2,087,658 inhabitants as of 2023.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The history of the area is closely linked to that of Provence.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Marseille has been an important harbour since before Julius Caesar's conquest of Gaul.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The Roman presence left numerous monuments across the department.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Notable people born in the area include Romantic painter Camille Roqueplan and his brother, journalist and theatre director Nestor Roqueplan.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Bouches-du-Rhône is one of the original 83 departments created during the French Revolution on 4 March 1790.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] It was created from the western part of the former province of Provence and the principalities of Orange, Martigues and Lambesc.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] It lost part of its territory in 1793, including Orange and Apt, when the department of Vaucluse was created.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Following its creation, the department strongly supported the French Revolution, containing 90 Jacobin Clubs by 1794.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] It was also noteworthy that more than half of the priests in the department accepted the Civil Constitution of the Clergy, which in effect subordinated the church to the government.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The department is part of the current region of Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] It is surrounded by the departments of Gard on the west, Vaucluse on the north and Var on the east, as well as by the Mediterranean Sea on the south.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The Rhône river delta forms a vast swampy wetlands area called the Camargue in the southwestern part of the department.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The Rove Tunnel, the world's longest canal tunnel from Marseille to the Étang de Berre, as well as smaller canals further west, allowed for waterway transport from Marseille to the Rhône until 1963, when the Rove Tunnel closed to traffic.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Bouches-du-Rhône is bordered by the rivers Rhône to the west and Durance to the north.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The Rhône divides into the *Grand Rhône* and *Petit Rhône* south of Arles; the area between forms the Camargue.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The principal mountains of the department are the Sainte-Baume massif (1,042 metres – 3,418 feet), Montagne Sainte-Victoire (1,011 metres – 3,316 feet), the Garlaban and Alpilles massifs.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The department of Bouches-du-Rhône is also known for its seismic activity: the zone II ("average seismic activity") townships of Lambesc Peyrolles-en-Provence and Salon-de-Provence are the most exposed.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Zone 0 ("negligible seismic activity") includes the rest of the department.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The department has a Mediterranean climate, with contrasting temperatures within a range of 15 degrees.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Precipitation is irregular, with only 65 days per year where rain falls in excess of 1 mm.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] However it falls in sudden downpours, with an average of 500–700 millimetres (20–28 inches) annually.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] This mainly happens in the spring and autumn; summer is very hot, winter mild.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Violent winds are common, especially the mistral, which blows 100 days per year with a maximum of 100 km/h (62 mph).
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The coast is drier, especially along the Côte Bleue, the Calanques and the bay of La Ciotat, which include some of the driest areas in France, with only 450 mm (18 in) of rain per year.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Higher areas receive more precipitation and lower temperatures.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The Arc region in the interior is much colder than other areas, with heavy frosts in winter.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The most populous commune is Marseille, the prefecture.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] There are 9 more communes with over 15,000 inhabitants: Les Pennes-Mirabeau, Gardanne, Allauch, Châteauneuf-les-Martigues, Châteaurenard, Fos-sur-Mer, Port-de-Bouc, Tarascon and Bouc-Bel-Air.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Since Bouches-du-Rhône is one of the most populous and diverse departments of France, it has long been the scene of particularly fierce political battles.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] From the late 19th century, the socialist movement gained influence, such as in 1881 by the election of the country's first socialist member of parliament, Clovis Hugues.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Rural areas, particularly in the region of Aix-en-Provence, have tended to favour the influence of right-wing parties, including monarchists and Catholics at the beginning of the French Third Republic.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The interwar period and the time of the Popular Front marked the beginning of the dominance of the left in the department, first with the election of the French Section of the Workers' International (SFIO).
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] After the Second World War, the Marseillais right, linked to the underworld and who collaborated with the German occupation, was widely discredited.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The left largely dominated the Liberation and Marseille even saw the election in 1946 of Communist Mayor Jean Cristofol.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] In 1947 the SFIO led an alliance with right and centre parties against the Communists, resulting six years later in the election of Gaston Defferre as Mayor of Marseille, a position he held until his death in 1986.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The dominance of socialism was, however, challenged by deindustrialisation.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The conservative success in 1995 by Jean-Claude Gaudin in Marseille is a symbol of widespread political shifts while even the former communists bastions of La Ciotat and Port-Saint-Louis-du-Rhône voted for the right.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The 1990s saw the rise of the National Front, including its victories in municipal elections of Marignane and Vitrolles.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The President of the Departmental Council has been Martine Vassal of the right-wing The Republicans party since 2015, after former Socialist President Jean-Noël Guérini was voted out of office and has faced corruption charges.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] In the 2022 French presidential election, just like five years prior, Marine Le Pen of the National Rally (formerly National Front) won a majority in Bouches-du-Rhône in the first round, before incumbent Emmanuel Macron of La République En Marche! won a majority in the second round.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Below is a list of seats won by the department's different parties after the 2015 departmental elections.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The department is well represented in French art.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Paul Cézanne painted numerous representations of the Mont Sainte-Victoire.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Vincent van Gogh spent two years in Arles, painting many scenes in the area.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The department's main museums include the Museum of European and Mediterranean Civilisations, the Musée de la Faïence de Marseille and the Marseille History Museum.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] The department is served by Marseille Provence Airport which provides direct routes to other parts of France, Europe, northern Africa, Asia and northern America.
[src:château-des-baux/bouches-du-rhône] Nice Côte d'Azur Airport is also fairly used by air travellers from the department.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The **mangonel**, also called the **traction trebuchet**, was a type of trebuchet used in Ancient China starting from the Warring States period, and later across Eurasia by the 6th century AD.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Unlike the later counterweight trebuchet, the mangonel was operated by people pulling ropes attached to one end of a lever, the other end of which had a sling to launch projectiles.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Although the mangonel required more men to function, it was also less complex and faster to reload than the torsion-powered onager which it replaced in early Medieval Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] It was replaced as the primary siege weapon in the 12th and 13th centuries by the counterweight trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] A common misconception about the mangonel is that it was a torsion siege engine.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The word *mangonel* was first attested in English in the 13th century, it is borrowed from Old French *mangonel*, *mangonelle* (> French *mangonneau*).
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Mangonel was a general term for medieval stone-throwing artillery and was used more specifically to refer to manually (traction--) powered weapons.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] It is sometimes wrongly used to refer to the onager.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Modern military historians came up with the term "traction trebuchet" to distinguish it from previous torsion machines such as the onager.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The mangonel was called *al-manjanīq*, *arrada*, *shaytani*, or *sultani* in Arabic.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] In China, the mangonel was called the *pào* (砲).
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The mangonel originated in ancient China.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Torsion-based siege weapons such as the ballista and onager are not known to have been used in China.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The first recorded use of mangonels was in ancient China.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] They were probably used by the Mohists as early as 4th century BC; descriptions can be found in the *Mozi* (compiled in the 4th century BC).
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] They were used as defensive weapons stationed on walls and sometimes hurled hollowed out logs filled with burning charcoal to destroy enemy siege works.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] They were commonly called stone-throwing machines, thunder carriages, and stone carriages in the following centuries.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] They were used as ship mounted weapons by the year 573 for attacking enemy fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] It seems that during the early 7th century, improvements were made on mangonels, although it is not explicitly stated what.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] According to a stele in Barkul celebrating Tang Taizong's conquest of what is now Ejin Banner, the engineer Jiang Xingben made great advancements on mangonels that were unknown in ancient times.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Jiang Xingben participated in the construction of siege engines for Taizong's campaigns against the Western Regions.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] During the Jingde period (1004–1007), many young men rose in office due to their military accomplishments, and one such man, Zhang Cun, was said to have possessed no knowledge except how to operate a Whirlwind mangonel.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] When the Jurchen Jin dynasty (1115–1234) laid siege to Kaifeng in 1126, they attacked with 5,000 mangonels.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The mangonel was adopted by various peoples west of China such as the Byzantines, Persians, Arabs, and Avars by the sixth to seventh centuries AD.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Some scholars suggest that Avars carried the mangonel westward while others claim that the Byzantines already possessed knowledge of the mangonel beforehand.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Regardless of the vector of transmission, it appeared in the eastern Mediterranean by the late 6th century AD, where it replaced torsion powered siege engines such as the ballista and onager.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The rapid displacement of torsion siege engines was probably due to a combination of reasons.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The mangonel is simpler in design, has a faster rate of fire, increased accuracy, and comparable range and power.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] According to the *Miracles of Saint Demetrius*, probably written around 620 by John, Archbishop of Thessaloniki, the Avaro-Slavs attacked Thessaloniki in 586 with more than 50 mangonels.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The bombardment lasted for hours, but the operators were inaccurate and most of the shots missed their target.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] When one stone did reach their target, it "demolished the top of the rampart down to the walkway." The *Miracles* does not provide a clear date of the siege, which could have been in 586 or 597.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] An argument has been made that the Byzantines were already acquainted with mangonels prior to this based on the *History* written by Theophylact Simocatta in the late 620s.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The account describes a captured Byzantine soldier named Busas who taught the Avars how to construct a "besieging machine" which led to their conquest of Appiaria in 587.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The word used for the machine is *helepolis*, which does not indicate a specific siege engine.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] It has been variously interpreted as a battering ram, a stone-throwing trebuchet, and a siege tower.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Theophylact's account is vague on descriptions of the device and why it allowed the Avars to take Appiaria after they had already taken many Roman cities beforehand.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Greek term *manganikon*, from which the Arabic word for trebuchet *mandjanik* is derived, was also first used to describe Avar machines used against Constantinople in 626.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Peter Purton notes that the account by Theophylact is not contemporary and likely written when the mangonel was more common.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] David Graff and Purton argue that the account by Theophylact has chronological problems and does not explain why the machine used by the Avars in the *Miracles* was treated as a novelty in either 586 or 597, since the Byzantines would have known about it in both cases.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Yet there are no descriptions of the mangonel in the west prior to the encounter with the Avars.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Purton considers it equally likely for the Avars, Byzantines, or Persians to have learned of the mangonel first in the western world.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Michael Fulton says it is at least equally likely that the Avars or some other vector transmitted the technology to the Byzantines, but expressed skepticism that the mangonel was complex enough to require explanation by a captured Byzantine soldier.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] He described Theophylact's account as a "racially motivated explanation of how a supposedly 'barbaric' people were able to replicate and incorporate a piece of 'civilised' technology".
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Others like Stephen McCotter and John Haldon consider the Avar theory to be the most likely.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Byzantines may have used the mangonel in 587 against a Persian fort near Akbas, although the operators did not seem to have handled it very effectively, suggesting that it was still a new weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Persians may have used mangonels against Dara in the early 7th century and against Jerusalem in 614.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Arabs had ship mounted mangonel by 653 and used them at Mecca in 683.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Franks and Saxons adopted the weapon in the 8th century.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The *Life of Louis the Pious* contains the earliest western European reference to mangonels in its account of the siege of Tortosa (808–809).
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] In the 890s, Abbo Cernuus described *mango* or *manganaa* used at the Siege of Paris (885–886) which had high posts, presumably meaning they used trebuchet-type throwing arms.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] In 1173, the Republic of Pisa tried to capture an island castle with mangonels on galleys.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] According to Leife Inge Ree Peterson, a mangonel could have been used at Theodosiopolis in 421 but was "likely an onager".
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Peterson says that mangonels may have been independently invented or at least known in the Eastern Mediterranean by 500 AD based on records of different and better artillery weapons, however there is no explicit description of a mangonel.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] According to Peterson's timeline and presumption that the mangonel became widespread throughout the Roman Empire by the mid-6th century, mangonels would also have been used in Spain and Italy by the mid 6th century, in Africa by the 7th century, and by the Franks in the 8th century.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Tracy Rihll suggests that the mangonel was independently invented through an evolution of the Byzantine staff-sling, although this has received little support.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] There are no sources indicating whether Byzantium received the mangonel from East Asia or if it was independently invented.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The mangonel was most efficient as an anti-personnel weapon, used in a supportive position alongside archers and slingers.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Most accounts of mangonels describe them as light artillery weapons while actual penetration of defenses was the result of mining or siege towers.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] At the Siege of Kamacha in 766, Byzantine defenders used wooden cover to protect themselves from the enemy artillery while inflicting casualties with their stone throwers.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Michael the Syrian noted that at the siege of Balis in 823 it was the defenders that suffered from bombardment rather than the fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] At the siege of Kaysum, Abdallah ibn Tahir al-Khurasani used artillery to damage houses in the town.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Sack of Amorium in 838 saw the use of mangonels to drive away defenders and destroy wooden defenses.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Some exceptionally large and powerful mangonels have been described during the 11th century or later.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] At the Siege of Manzikert (1054), the Seljuks' initial siege artillery was countered by the defenders' own, which shot stones at the besieging machine.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] In response, the Seljuks constructed another one requiring 400 men to pull and throw stones weighing 20 kilograms (44 lb).
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] A breach was created on the first shot but the machine was burnt down by the defenders.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] According to Matthew of Edessa, this machine weighed 3,400 kilograms (7,500 lb) and caused several casualties to the city's defenders.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Ibn al-Adim describes a mangonel capable of throwing a man in 1089.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] At the siege of Haizhou in 1161, a mangonel was reported to have had a range of 200 paces (over 400 m (1,300 ft)).
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] West of China, the mangonel remained the primary siege engine until the late 12th century when it was replaced by the counterweight trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] In China the mangonel was the primary siege engine until the counterweight trebuchet was introduced during the Mongol conquest of the Song dynasty in the 13th century.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The counterweight trebuchet did not completely replace the mangonel.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Despite its greater range, counterweight trebuchets had to be constructed close to the site of the siege unlike mangonels, which were smaller, lighter, cheaper, and easier to take apart and put back together again where necessary.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The superiority of the counterweight trebuchet was not clear cut.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Of this, the Hongwu Emperor stated in 1388: "The old type of trebuchet was really more convenient.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] If you have a hundred of those machines, then when you are ready to march, each wooden pole can be carried by only four men.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Then when you reach your destination, you encircle the city, set them up, and start shooting!" The mangonel continued to serve as an anti-personnel weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Norwegian text of 1240, *Speculum regale*, explicitly states this division of functions.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] Mangonels were to be used for hitting people in undefended areas.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] As late as the Siege of Acre (1291), where the Mamluk Sultanate fielded 72 or 92 trebuchets, the majority were still mangonels while 14 or 15 were counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The counterweight trebuchets were unable to create a breach in Acre's walls and the Mamluks entered the city by sapping the northeast corner of the outer wall.
[src:château-des-baux/bricole] The Templar of Tyre described the faster firing mangonels as more dangerous to the defenders than the counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The **Bronze Age** is an archaeological and anthropological term defining a phase in the development of material culture among ancient societies in Asia, the Near East and Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] An ancient civilisation or culture is deemed to be part of the Bronze Age if it either produced bronze by smelting its own copper and alloying it with tin, arsenic, or other metals, or traded other items for bronze from producing areas elsewhere.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Bronze Age is the middle principal period of the three-age system, following the Stone Age and preceding the Iron Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Conceived as a global era, the Bronze Age follows the Neolithic ("New Stone") period, with a transition period between the two known as the Chalcolithic ("copper-Stone") Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] These technical developments took place at different times in different places, and therefore each region's history is framed by a different chronological system, but the Bronze Age had begun in much of the Old World by 3,000 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bronze Age cultures were the first to develop writing.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] According to archaeological evidence, cultures in Mesopotamia, which used cuneiform script, and Egypt, which used hieroglyphs, developed the earliest practical writing systems.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In a particular region, whichever comes first of the arrival of the Iron Age, or the development of writing, is usually taken to mark the end of the Bronze Age, as history replaces prehistory; this is not always the case in the earliest areas to develop writing.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In the archaeology of the Americas, a five-period system is conventionally used instead, which does not include a Bronze Age, though some cultures there did smelt copper and bronze.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] No evidence of metalworking has been found on the Australian continent prior to the establishment of European settlements in 1788.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In many areas bronze continued to be rare and expensive, mainly because of difficulties in obtaining enough tin, which occurs in relatively few places, unlike the very common copper.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] It is likely that the earliest tin deposits were alluvial and perhaps exploited by the same methods used for panning gold in placer deposits.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Some societies appear to have gone through much of the Bronze Age using bronze only for weapons or elite art, such as Chinese ritual bronzes, with ordinary farmers largely still using stone tools.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, this is hard to assess as the rarity of bronze meant it was keenly recycled.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bronze Age civilisations gained a technological advantage due to bronze's harder and more durable properties than other metals available at the time.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] While terrestrial iron is naturally abundant, the higher temperature required for smelting, 1,250 °C (2,280 °F), in addition to the greater difficulty of working with it, placed it out of reach of common use until the end of the 2nd millennium BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Tin's lower melting point of 232 °C (450 °F) and copper's moderate melting point of 1,085 °C (1,985 °F) placed both these metals within the capabilities of Neolithic pottery kilns, which date to 6000 BC and were able to produce temperatures of at least 900 °C (1,650 °F).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Bronze Age is characterised by the widespread use of bronze, though the introduction and development of bronze technology were not universally synchronous.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bronze was independently discovered in the Maykop culture of the North Caucasus as early as the mid-4th millennium BC, which makes them the producers of the oldest-known bronze.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, the Maykop culture only had arsenical bronze.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Other regions developed bronze and its associated technology at different periods.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Tin bronze technology requires systematic techniques: tin must be mined (mainly as the tin ore cassiterite) and smelted separately, then added to hot copper to make bronze alloy.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Bronze Age was a time of extensive use of metals and the development of trade networks.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] A 2013 report suggests that the earliest tin-alloy bronze was a foil dated to the mid-5th millennium BC from a Vinča culture site in Pločnik, Serbia, although this culture is not conventionally considered part of the Bronze Age; however, the dating of the foil has been disputed.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] West Asia and the Near East were the first regions to enter the Bronze Age, beginning with the rise of the Mesopotamian civilization of Sumer in the mid-4th millennium BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Societies in the region laid the foundations for astronomy, mathematics, and astrology.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Bronze Age in the Near East can be divided into Early, Middle and Late periods.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The dates and phases below apply solely to the Near East, not universally.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, some archaeologists propose a "high chronology", which extends periods such as the Intermediate Bronze Age by 300 to 500–600 years, based on material analysis of the southern Levant in cities such as Hazor, Jericho, and Beit She'an.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Hittite Empire was established during the 18th century BC in Hattusa, northern Anatolia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] At its height in the 14th century BC, the Hittite Kingdom encompassed central Anatolia, southwestern Syria as far as Ugarit, and upper Mesopotamia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] After 1180 BC, amid general turmoil in the Levant, which is conjectured to have been associated with the sudden arrival of the Sea Peoples, the kingdom disintegrated into several independent "Neo-Hittite" city-states, some of which survived into the 8th century BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Arzawa, in Western Anatolia, during the second half of the 2nd millennium BC, likely extended along southern Anatolia in a belt from near the Turkish Lakes region to the Aegean coast.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Arzawa was the western neighbour of the Middle and New Hittite Kingdoms, at times a rival and, at other times, a vassal.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Assuwa league was a confederation of states in western Anatolia defeated by the Hittites under the earlier Tudhaliya I c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Arzawa has been associated with the more obscure Assuwa generally located to its north.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] It probably bordered it, and may have been an alternative term for it during some periods.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In Ancient Egypt, the Bronze Age began in the Protodynastic Period c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The archaic *Early Bronze Age of Egypt*, known as the Early Dynastic Period of Egypt, immediately followed the unification of Lower and Upper Egypt, c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] It is generally taken to include the First and Second dynasties, lasting from the Protodynastic Period until c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 2686 BC, or the beginning of the Old Kingdom.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] With the First Dynasty, the capital moved from Abydos to Memphis with a unified Egypt ruled by an Egyptian god-king.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Abydos remained the major holy land in the south.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The hallmarks of ancient Egyptian civilization, such as art, architecture and religion, took shape in the Early Dynastic Period.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Memphis, in the Early Bronze Age, was the largest city of the time.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The First Intermediate Period of Egypt, often described as a "dark period" in ancient Egyptian history, spanned about 100 years after the end of the Old Kingdom from about 2181 to 2055 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Very little monumental evidence survives from this period, especially from the early part of it.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The First Intermediate Period was a dynamic time when the rule of Egypt was roughly divided between two areas: Heracleopolis in Lower Egypt and Thebes in Upper Egypt.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] These two kingdoms eventually came into conflict, and the Theban kings conquered the north, reunifying Egypt under a single ruler during the second part of the Eleventh Dynasty.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Bronze Age in Nubia started as early as 2300 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Egyptians introduced copper smelting to the Nubian city of Meroë in present-day Sudan c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] A furnace for bronze casting found in Kerma has been dated to 2300–1900 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Middle Kingdom of Egypt spanned between 2055 and 1650 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] During this period, the Osiris funerary cult rose to dominate popular Ancient Egyptian religion.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The period comprises two phases: the Eleventh Dynasty, which ruled from Thebes, and the Twelfth and Thirteenth dynasties, centred on el-Lisht.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The unified kingdom was previously considered to comprise the Eleventh and Twelfth Dynasties, but historians now consider part of the Thirteenth Dynasty to have belonged to the Middle Kingdom.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] During the Second Intermediate Period, Ancient Egypt fell into disarray a second time between the end of the Middle Kingdom and the start of the New Kingdom, best known for the Hyksos, whose reign comprised the Fifteenth and Sixteenth dynasties.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Hyksos first appeared in Egypt during the Eleventh Dynasty, began their climb to power in the Thirteenth Dynasty, and emerged from the Second Intermediate Period in control of Avaris and the Nile Delta.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] By the Fifteenth Dynasty, they ruled lower Egypt.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] They were expelled at the end of the Seventeenth Dynasty.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The New Kingdom of Egypt, also referred to as the Egyptian Empire, existed during the 16th–11th centuries BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The New Kingdom followed the Second Intermediate Period and was succeeded by the Third Intermediate Period.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] It was Egypt's most prosperous time and marked the peak of Egypt's power.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The later New Kingdom, comprising the Nineteenth and Twentieth dynasties (1292–1069 BC), is also known as the Ramesside period, after the eleven pharaohs who took the name of Ramesses.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Elam was a pre-Iranian ancient civilization located east of Mesopotamia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In the Middle Bronze Age, Elam consisted of kingdoms on the Iranian plateau, centred in Anshan.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] From the mid-2nd millennium BC, Elam was centered in Susa in the Khuzestan lowlands.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Its culture played a crucial role in both the Gutian Empire and the Iranian Achaemenid dynasty that succeeded it.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Oxus civilization was a Bronze Age Central Asian culture dated c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 2300–1700 BC and centred on the upper Amu Darya (a.k.a. the Oxus).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In the Early Bronze Age, the culture of the Kopet Dag oases and Altyndepe developed a proto-urban society.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] This corresponds to level IV at Namazga-Tepe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The height of this urban development was reached in the Middle Bronze Age c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 2300 BC, corresponding to level V at Namazga-Depe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] This Bronze Age culture is called the Bactria–Margiana Archaeological Complex.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Kulli culture, similar to that of the Indus Valley Civilisation, was located in southern Balochistan (Gedrosia) c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Dams were found in several places, providing evidence for a highly developed water management system.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Konar Sandal is associated with the hypothesized Jiroft culture, a 3rd-millennium BC culture postulated based on a collection of artefacts confiscated in 2001.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The term *Neo-Syria* is used to designate the early Iron Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The old Syrian period was dominated by the Eblaite first kingdom, Nagar and the Mariote second kingdom.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Akkadians conquered large areas of the Levant and were followed by the Amorite kingdoms, c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 2000–1600 BC, which arose in Mari, Yamhad, Qatna, and Assyria.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] From the 15th century BC onward, the term Amurru is usually applied to the region extending north of Canaan as far as Kadesh on the Orontes River.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The earliest-known contact of Ugarit with Egypt (and the first exact dating of Ugaritic civilisation) comes from a carnelian bead identified with the Middle Kingdom pharaoh Senusret I, whose reign is dated to 1971–1926 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] A stela and a statuette of the Egyptian pharaohs Senusret III and Amenemhet III have also been found.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, it is unclear when they first arrived at Ugarit.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In the Amarna letters, messages from Ugarit c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 1350 BC written by Ammittamru I, Niqmaddu II, and his queen have been discovered.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] From the 16th to the 13th century BC, Ugarit remained in constant contact with Egypt and Cyprus (Alashiya).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Mitanni was a loosely organised state in northern Syria and south-east Anatolia, emerging c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Founded by an Indo-Aryan ruling class that governed a predominantly Hurrian population, Mitanni came to be a regional power after the Hittite destruction of Kassite Babylon created a power vacuum in Mesopotamia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] At its beginning, Mitanni's major rival was Egypt under the Thutmosids.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, with the ascent of the Hittite empire, Mitanni and Egypt allied to protect their mutual interests from the threat of Hittite domination.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] At the height of its power during the 14th century BC, Mitanni had outposts centred on its capital, Washukanni, which archaeologists have located on the headwaters of the Khabur River.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Eventually, Mitanni succumbed to the Hittites and later Assyrian attacks, eventually being reduced to a province of the Middle Assyrian Empire.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Israelites were an ancient Semitic-speaking people of the Ancient Near East who inhabited part of Canaan during the tribal and monarchic periods (15th–6th centuries BC), and lived in the region in smaller numbers after the fall of the monarchy.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 1209 BC, at the end of the Late Bronze Age and the very beginning of the Iron Age, on the Merneptah Stele raised by the Egyptian pharaoh Merneptah.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Arameans were a Northwest Semitic semi-nomadic pastoral people who originated in what is now modern Syria (Biblical Aram) during the Late Bronze and early Iron Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Large groups migrated to Mesopotamia, where they intermingled with the native Akkadian (Assyrian and Babylonian) population.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Aramaeans never had a unified empire; they were divided into independent kingdoms all across the Near East.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] After the Bronze Age collapse, their political influence was confined to Syro-Hittite states, which were entirely absorbed into the Neo-Assyrian Empire by the 8th century BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 3500 BC and ended with the Kassite period (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The usual tripartite division into an Early, Middle and Late Bronze Age is not used in the context of Mesopotamia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Instead, a division primarily based on art and historical characteristics is more common.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The cities of the Ancient Near East housed several tens of thousands of people.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Ur, Kish, Isin, Larsa, and Nippur in the Middle Bronze Age and Babylon, Calah, and Assur in the Late Bronze Age similarly had large populations.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Akkadian Empire (2335–2154 BC) became the dominant power in the region.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] After its fall, the Sumerians enjoyed a renaissance with the Neo-Sumerian Empire.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Assyria, along with the Old Assyrian Empire (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 1800–1600 BC), became a regional power under the Amorite king Shamshi-Adad I.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The earliest mention of Babylon (then a small administrative town) appears on a tablet from the reign of Sargon of Akkad in the 23rd century BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Amorite dynasty established the city-state of Babylon in the 19th century BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Over a century later, it briefly took over the other city-states and formed the short-lived First Babylonian Empire during what is also called the Old Babylonian Period.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Akkad, Assyria, and Babylonia used the written East Semitic Akkadian language for official use and as a spoken language.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] By that time, the Sumerian language was no longer spoken, but was still in religious use in Assyria and Babylonia, and would remain so until the 1st century AD.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Akkadian and Sumerian traditions played a major role in later Assyrian and Babylonian culture.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Despite this, Babylonia, unlike the more militarily powerful Assyria, was founded by non-native Amorites and often ruled by other non-indigenous peoples such as the Kassites, Aramaeans and Chaldeans, as well as by its Assyrian neighbours.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] For many decades, scholars made superficial reference to Central Asia as the "pastoral realm" or alternatively, the "nomadic world", in what researchers call the "Central Asian void": a 5,000-year span that was neglected in studies of the origins of agriculture.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Foothill regions and glacial melt streams supported Bronze Age agro-pastoralists who developed complex east–west trade routes between Central Asia and China that introduced wheat and barley to China and millet to Central Asia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Bactria–Margiana Archaeological Complex (BMAC), also known as the Oxus civilisation, was a Bronze Age civilisation in Central Asia, dated c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 1600 BC, located in present-day northern Afghanistan, eastern Turkmenistan, southern Uzbekistan and western Tajikistan, centred on the upper Amu Darya (Oxus River).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Its sites were discovered and named by the Soviet archaeologist Viktor Sarianidi (1976).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bactria was the Greek name for the area of Bactra (modern Balkh), in what is now northern Afghanistan, and Margiana was the Greek name for the Persian satrapy of Marguš, the capital of which was Merv in present-day Turkmenistan.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] A wealth of information indicates that the BMAC had close international relations with the Indus Valley, the Iranian plateau, and possibly even indirectly with Mesopotamia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] All civilisations were familiar with lost wax casting.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] According to a 2019 study, the BMAC was not a primary contributor to later South-Asian genetics.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Altai Mountains, marking a natural boundary between Siberia and Mongolia, have been identified as the point of origin of a cultural enigma termed the Seima-Turbino Phenomenon.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] It is conjectured that changes in climate in this region c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 2000 BC, and the ensuing ecological, economic, and political changes, triggered a rapid and massive migration westward into northeast Europe, eastward into China, and southward into Vietnam and Thailand across a frontier of some 4,000 mi (6,000 km).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] This migration took place in just five to six generations and led to peoples from Finland in the west to Thailand in the east employing the same metalworking technology and, in some areas, horse breeding and riding.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, genetic testings of sites in south Siberia and Kazakhstan (Andronovo horizon) would rather support spreading of the bronze technology via Indo-European migrations eastwards, as this technology had been well known for quite a while in western regions.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] It is further conjectured that the same migrations spread the Uralic group of languages across Europe and Asia, with extant members of the family including Hungarian, Finnish and Estonian.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In China, the earliest bronze artefacts have been found in the Majiayao culture site (3100–2700 BC).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The term "Bronze Age" has been transferred to the archaeology of China from that of Western Eurasia, and there is no consensus or universally used convention delimiting the "Bronze Age" in the context of Chinese prehistory.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Together with the jade art that precedes it, bronze was seen as a fine material for ritual art when compared with iron or stone.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bronze metallurgy in China originated in what is referred to as the Erlitou period, which some historians argue places it within the Shang.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Others believe the Erlitou sites belong to the preceding Xia dynasty.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The United States National Gallery of Art defines the Chinese Bronze Age as c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 771 BC, a period that begins with the Erlitou culture and ends abruptly with the disintegration of Western Zhou rule.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] There is reason to believe that bronze work developed inside of China apart from outside influence.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, the discovery of the Europoid Tarim mummies in Xinjiang has caused some archaeologists such as Johan Gunnar Andersson, Jan Romgard, and An Zhimin to suggest a possible route of transmission from the West eastwards.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, the oldest bronze objects found in China so far were discovered at the Majiayao site in Gansu rather than at Xinjiang.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The production of Erlitou represents the earliest large-scale metallurgy industry in the Central Plains of China.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The metallurgical centres of northwestern China, especially the Qijia culture in Gansu and Longshan culture in Shaanxi, played an intermediary role in this process.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Iron use in China dates as early as the Zhou dynasty (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Chinese literature authored during the 6th century BC attests to knowledge of iron smelting, yet bronze continues to occupy the seat of significance in the archaeological and historical record for some time after this.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] White argues that iron did not supplant bronze "at any period before the end of the Zhou dynasty (256 BC)" and that bronze vessels make up the majority of metal vessels through the Eastern Han period, or to 221 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Chinese bronze artefacts generally are either utilitarian, like spear points or adze heads, or "ritual bronzes", which are more elaborate versions in precious materials of everyday vessels, as well as tools and weapons.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Examples are the numerous large sacrificial tripods known as *dings*; there are many other distinct shapes.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Surviving identified Chinese ritual bronzes tend to be highly decorated, often with the *taotie* motif, which involves stylised animal faces.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] These appear in three main motif types: those of demons, symbolic animals, and abstract symbols.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Many large bronzes also bear cast inscriptions that are the bulk of the surviving body of early Chinese writing and have helped historians and archaeologists piece together the history of China, especially during the Zhou dynasty.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The bronzes of the Western Zhou document large portions of history not found in the extant texts that were often composed by persons of varying rank and possibly even social class.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Further, the medium of cast bronze lends the record they preserve a permanence not enjoyed by manuscripts.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] These inscriptions can commonly be subdivided into four parts: a reference to the date and place, the naming of the event commemorated, the list of gifts given to the artisan in exchange for the bronze, and a dedication.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The relative points of reference these vessels provide have enabled historians to place most of the vessels within a certain time frame of the Western Zhou period, allowing them to trace the evolution of the vessels and the events they record.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Japanese archipelago saw the introduction of bronze during the early Yayoi period (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 300 BC), which saw the introduction of metalworking and agricultural practices brought by settlers arriving from the continent.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bronze and iron smelting spread to the Japanese archipelago through contact with other ancient East Asian civilisations, particularly immigration and trade from the ancient Korean peninsula, and ancient mainland China.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Iron was mainly used for agricultural and other tools, whereas ritual and ceremonial artefacts were mainly made of bronze.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bronze weapons such as daggers, halberds, and spearheads at first functioned as weapons then later into the Yayoi period evolved into impractical ritual objects.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] On the Korean Peninsula, the Bronze Age began c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Initially centred around Liaoning and southern Manchuria, Korean Bronze Age culture exhibits unique typology and styles, especially in ritual objects.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Mumun pottery period is named after the Korean name for undecorated or plain cooking and storage vessels that form a large part of the pottery assemblage over the entire length of the period, but especially between 850 and 550 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Mumun period is known for the origins of intensive agriculture and complex societies in both the Korean Peninsula and the Japanese Archipelago.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Middle Mumun pottery period culture of the southern Korean Peninsula gradually adopted bronze production (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 700–600 BC after a period when Liaoning-style bronze daggers and other bronze artefacts were exchanged as far as the interior part of the Southern Peninsula (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The bronze daggers lent prestige and authority to the personages who wielded and were buried with them in high-status megalithic burials at south-coastal centres such as the Igeum-dong site.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Bronze was an important element in ceremonies and for mortuary offerings until 100 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Bronze Age on the Indian subcontinent began c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] 3300 BC with the beginning of the Indus Valley Civilization.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Inhabitants of the Indus Valley, the Harappans, developed new techniques in metallurgy and produced copper, bronze, lead, and tin.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Late Harappan culture (1900–1400 BC), overlapped the transition from the Bronze Age to the Iron Age; thus it is difficult to date this transition accurately.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] It has been claimed that a 6,000-year-old copper amulet manufactured in Mehrgarh in the shape of a wheel spoke is the earliest example of lost-wax casting in the world.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The civilisation's cities were noted for their urban planning, baked brick houses, elaborate drainage systems, water supply systems, clusters of large non-residential buildings, and new techniques in handicraft (carnelian products, seal carving) and metallurgy (copper, bronze, lead, and tin).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The large cities of Mohenjo-daro and Harappa likely grew to contain between 30,000 and 60,000 people, and the civilisation during its florescence may have contained between one and five million people.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Vilabouly Complex in Laos is a significant archaeological site for dating the origin of bronze metallurgy in Southeast Asia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In Ban Chiang, Thailand, bronze artefacts have been discovered that date to 2100 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] However, according to the radiocarbon dating on the human and pig bones in Ban Chiang, some scholars propose that the initial Bronze Age in Ban Chiang was in the late 2nd millennium.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] In Nyaung-gan, Myanmar, bronze tools have been excavated along with ceramics and stone artefacts.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Dating is still currently broad (2300–500 BC).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Ban Non Wat, excavated by Charles Higham, was a rich site with over 640 graves excavated that gleaned many complex bronze items that may have had social value connected to them.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Ban Chiang, however, is the most thoroughly documented site and has the clearest evidence of metallurgy when in Southeast Asia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] With a rough date range from the late 3rd millennium BC to the 1st millennium AD, this site has artefacts such as burial pottery (dated 2100–1700 BC) and fragments of bronze and copper-base bangles.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] This technology suggested on-site casting from the beginning.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The on-site casting supports the theory that bronze was first introduced in Southeast Asia from a different country.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Some scholars believe that copper-based metallurgy was disseminated from northwest and central China south and southwest via areas such as Guangdong and Yunnan and finally into southeast Asia c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Archaeology also suggests that Bronze Age metallurgy may not have been as significant a catalyst in social stratification and warfare in Southeast Asia as in other regions, and that social distribution shifted away from chiefdoms to a heterarchical network.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Data analyses of sites such as Ban Lum Khao, Ban Na Di, Non-Nok Tha, Khok Phanom Di, and Nong Nor have consistently led researchers to conclude that there was no entrenched hierarchy.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Dating to the Neolithic, the first bronze drums, called the Dong Son drums, were uncovered in and around the Red River Delta regions of northern Vietnam and Southern China.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] These relate to the Dong Son culture of Vietnam.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Archaeological research in Northern Vietnam indicates an increase in rates of infectious disease following the advent of metallurgy; skeletal fragments in sites dating to the early and mid-Bronze Age evidence a greater proportion of lesions than in sites of earlier periods.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] There are a few possible implications of this.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] One is the increased contact with bacterial and/or fungal pathogens due to increased population density and land clearing/cultivation.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Another implication is decreased levels of immunocompetence in the Metal Age due to changes in diet caused by agriculture.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The last implication is that there may have been an emergence of infectious diseases that evolved into a more virulent form in the metal period.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The finding of bronze axes at Nyaunggan located in Shwebo township suggests that Bronze Age of Burma began around 1500 BC in parallel with the earlier stages of Southeast Asian bronze production.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] This period spans from 1500 to 1000 BC during which knowledge of the smelting and casting of copper and tin seems to have spread rapidly along the Neolithic exchange routes.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Another site is the area of Taungthaman, near Irrawaddy River within the walls of the 18th century capital, Amarapura, occupied from the late Neolithic through the early Iron Age, around the middle of the first millennium BCE.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] Small trades and barters, as well as Animism had already begun in this age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p01] The Taungthaman site was discovered in 1971 and bulldozed by the State Administration Council in 2023.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] A few examples of named Bronze Age cultures in Europe roughly in relative order—dates are approximate.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The chosen cultures overlapped in time and the indicated periods do not fully correspond to their estimated extents.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] (2013) reported the discovery of a tin bronze foil from the Pločnik archaeological site dated to c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 4650 BC as well as 14 other artefacts from Serbia and Bulgaria dated before 4000 BC, showing that early tin bronze was more common than previously thought and developed independently in Europe 1500 years before the first tin bronze alloys in the Near East.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The production of complex tin bronzes lasted for about 500 years in the Balkans.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The authors reported that evidence for the production of such complex bronzes disappears at the end of the 5th millennium BC, coinciding with the "collapse of large cultural complexes in north-eastern Bulgaria and Thrace".
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Tin bronzes using cassiterite tin were reintroduced to the area some 1500 years later.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The oldest golden artefacts in the world are dated between 4600 and 4200 BC, and were found in the Necropolis of Varna, Bulgaria.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] These artefacts are on display in the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Dabene Treasure was unearthed from 2004 to 2007 near Karlovo in central Bulgaria.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The treasure consists of 20,000 gold jewellery items from 18 to 23 carats.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The most important of them was a dagger made of gold and platinum with an unusual edge.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The treasure was dated to the end of the 3rd millennium BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Scientists suggest that the Karlovo Valley used to be a major crafts centre that exported golden jewellery across Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It is considered one of the largest prehistoric golden treasures in the world.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 3200 BC, when civilisations first established a far-ranging trade network.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] This network imported tin and charcoal to Cyprus, where copper was mined and alloyed with tin to produce bronze.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Bronze objects were then exported far and wide.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Isotopic analysis of tin in some Mediterranean bronze artefacts suggests that they may have originated from Bronze Age Britain.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Knowledge of navigation was well-developed by this time and reached a peak of skill not exceeded (except perhaps by Polynesian sailors) until 1730 when the invention of the chronometer enabled the precise determination of longitude.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Minoan civilisation based in Knossos on the island of Crete appears to have coordinated and defended its Bronze Age trade.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Ancient empires valued luxury goods in contrast to staple foods, leading to famine.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Bronze Age collapse theories have described aspects of the end of the Bronze Age in this region.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] At the end of the Bronze Age in the Aegean region, the Mycenaean administration of the regional trade empire followed the decline of Minoan primacy.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Several Minoan client states lost much of their population to famine and pestilence.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] This would indicate that the trade network may have failed, preventing the trade that would previously have relieved such famines and prevented illness caused by malnutrition.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It is also known that in this era, the breadbasket of the Minoan empire—the area north of the Black Sea—also suddenly lost much of its population and thus probably some capacity to cultivate crops.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Drought and famine in Anatolia may have also led to the Aegean collapse by disrupting trade networks, therefore preventing the Aegean from accessing bronze and luxury goods.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Aegean collapse has been attributed to the exhaustion of the Cypriot forests causing the end of the bronze trade.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] These forests are known to have existed in later times, and experiments have shown that charcoal production on the scale necessary for the bronze production of the late Bronze Age would have exhausted them in less than 50 years.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Aegean collapse has also been attributed to the fact that as iron tools became more common, the main justification for the tin trade ended, and that trade network ceased to function as it did formerly.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The colonies of the Minoan empire then suffered drought, famine, war, or some combination of the three, and had no access to the distant resources of an empire by which they could easily recover.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Speculation includes that a tsunami from Thera (more commonly known today as Santorini) destroyed Cretan cities.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] A tsunami may have destroyed the Cretan navy in its home harbour, which then lost crucial naval battles; so that in the LMIB/LMII event (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 1450 BC) the cities of Crete burned and the Mycenaean civilisation conquered Knossos.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] One such theory highlights the role of Cretan expertise in administering the empire, post-Thera.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] If this expertise was concentrated in Crete, then the Mycenaeans may have made political and commercial mistakes in administering the Cretan empire.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Archaeological findings, including some on the island of Thera, suggest that the centre of the Minoan civilisation at the time of the eruption was actually on Thera rather than on Crete.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] According to this theory, the catastrophic loss of the political, administrative and economic centre due to the eruption, as well as the damage wrought by the tsunami to the coastal towns and villages of Crete, precipitated the decline of the Minoans.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] A weakened political entity with a reduced economic and military capability and fabled riches would have then been more vulnerable to conquest.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Indeed, the Santorini eruption is usually dated to c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 1630 BC, while the Mycenaean Greeks first enter the historical record a few decades later, c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The later Mycenaean assaults on Crete (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 1250 BC) would have been a continuation of the steady encroachment of the Greeks upon the weakened Minoan world.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] In Central Europe, the Early Bronze Age Unetice culture (2300–1600 BC) includes numerous smaller groups like the Straubing, Adlerberg and Hatvan cultures.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Some very rich burials, such as the one located at Leubingen with grave gifts crafted from gold, point to an increase of social stratification already present in the Unetice culture.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Cemeteries of this period are small and rare.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Unetice culture was followed by the Middle Bronze Age (1600–1200 BC) tumulus culture, characterised by inhumation burials in tumuli barrows.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] In the eastern Hungarian Körös tributaries, the early Bronze Age first saw the introduction of the Mako culture, followed by the Otomani and Gyulavarsand cultures.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The late Bronze Age Urnfield culture (1300–700 BC) was characterised by cremation burials.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It included the Lusatian culture in eastern Germany and Poland (1300–500 BC) that continues into the Iron Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Central European Bronze Age was followed by the Iron Age Hallstatt culture (700–450 BC).
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Important sites include Biskupin in Poland, Nebra in Germany, Vráble in Slovakia, and Zug-Sumpf in Switzerland.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Apennine culture was a technology complex in central and southern Italy spanning both the Chalcolithic and Bronze Age proper.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Camuni were an ancient people of uncertain origin who lived in Val Camonica, in present-day Lombardy, during the Iron Age, although groups of hunters, shepherds, and farmers are known to have lived in the area since the Neolithic.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Located in Sardinia and Corsica, the Nuragic civilisation lasted from the early Bronze Age (18th century BC) to the 2nd century AD, when the islands were already Romanised.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] They take their name from the characteristic Nuragic towers, which evolved from the pre-existing megalithic culture, which built dolmens and menhirs.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The towers are unanimously considered the best-preserved and largest megalithic remains in Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Their purpose is still debated: some scholars consider them monumental tombs, others as Houses of the Giants, other as fortresses, ovens for metal fusion, prisons, or finally temples for a solar cult.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Near the end of the 3rd millennium BC, Sardinia exported to Sicily a culture that built small dolmens, trilithic or polygonal shaped, that served as tombs, as in the Sicilian dolmen of "Cava dei Servi".
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] From this region, they reached Malta and other countries of Mediterranean basin.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Terramare was an early Indo-European civilisation in the area of what is now Pianura Padana in northern Italy, before the arrival of the Celts, and in other parts of Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] They lived in square villages of wooden stilt houses.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] These villages were built on land, but generally near a stream, with roads forming a grid plan.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The whole complex was of the nature of a fortified settlement.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Terramare culture was widespread in the Pianura Padana, especially along the Panaro river, between Modena and Bologna, and in the rest of Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The civilisation developed in the Middle and Late Bronze Age during the 17th–13th centuries BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Castellieri culture developed in Istria during the Middle Bronze Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It lasted for more than a millennium, from the 15th century BC until the Roman conquest in the 3rd century BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It takes its name from the fortified boroughs (*Castellieri*, Friulian: *cjastelir*) that characterised the culture.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Canegrate culture developed from the mid-Bronze Age (13th century BC) until the Iron Age in the Pianura Padana, in what are now western Lombardy, eastern Piedmont, and Ticino.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It takes its name from the township of Canegrate, where, in the 20th century, some fifty tombs with ceramics and metal objects were found.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Canegrate culture migrated from the northwest part of the Alps and descended to Pianura Padana from the Swiss Alps passes and the Ticino.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Golasecca culture developed starting from the late Bronze Age in the Po plain.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It takes its name from Golasecca, a locality next to the Ticino, where in the early 19th century abbot Giovanni Battista Giani excavated its first findings comprising some 50 tombs with ceramics and metal objects.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Remains of the Golasecca culture span an area of about 20,000 km2 (4,900,000 acres) south to the Alps, between the Po, Sesia, and Serio rivers, dating to the 9th–4th centuries BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] In Great Britain, the Bronze Age is considered to have been the period from c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Migration brought new people to the islands from the continent.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Tooth enamel isotope research on bodies found in early Bronze Age graves around Stonehenge indicates that at least some of the migrants came from the area of present-day Switzerland.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Another example site is Must Farm near Whittlesey, host to the most complete Bronze Age wheel ever to be found.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Beaker culture displayed different behaviours from earlier Neolithic people, and cultural change was significant.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Integration is thought to have been peaceful, as many of the early henge sites were seemingly adopted by the newcomers.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The rich Wessex culture developed in southern Britain at this time.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Additionally, the climate was deteriorating; where once the weather was warm and dry it became much wetter as the Bronze Age continued, forcing the population away from easily defended sites in the hills and into the fertile valleys.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Large livestock farms developed in the lowlands and appear to have contributed to economic growth and inspired increasing forest clearances.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Deverel-Rimbury culture began to emerge in the second half of the Middle Bronze Age (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 1400–1100 BC) to exploit these conditions.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Devon and Cornwall were major sources of tin for much of western Europe and copper was extracted from sites such as the Great Orme mine in northern Wales.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Social groups appear to have been tribal but with growing complexity and hierarchies becoming apparent.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The burials, which until this period had usually been communal, became more individual.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] For example, whereas in the Neolithic a large chambered cairn or long barrow housed the dead, Early Bronze Age people buried their dead in individual barrows (commonly known and marked on modern British Ordnance Survey maps as tumuli), or sometimes in cists covered with cairns.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The greatest quantities of bronze objects in England were discovered in East Cambridgeshire, with the most important finds being the 6,500-piece Isleham Hoard.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Alloying of copper with tin to make bronze was practised soon after the discovery of copper.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The techniques needed to deliberately alloy copper with zinc to form brass first arrived in Great Britain late in the first millennium BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] One copper mine at Great Orme in North Wales, reached a depth of 70 metres.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] At Alderley Edge in Cheshire, carbon dating has established mining at around 2280 to 1890 BC with a 95% probability.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The earliest identified metalworking site (Sigwells, Somerset) came much later, dated by globular urn-style pottery to c. the 12th century BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The identifiable sherds from over 500 mould fragments included a perfect fit of the hilt of a sword in the Wilburton style held in Somerset County Museum.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Atlantic Bronze Age as cultural geographic region is a cultural complex (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It is marked by economic and cultural exchange.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Commercial contacts extend to Denmark and the Mediterranean.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Atlantic Bronze Age was defined by many distinct regional centres of metal production, unified by a regular maritime exchange of products.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 2000 BC when copper was alloyed with tin and used to manufacture Ballybeg type flat axes and associated metalwork.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The preceding period is known as the Copper Age and is characterised by the production of flat axes, daggers, halberds and awls in copper.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The period is divided into three phases: Early Bronze Age (2000–1500 BC), Middle Bronze Age (1500–1200 BC), and Late Bronze Age (1200 – c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Ireland is known for a relatively large number of Early Bronze Age burials.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The country's stone circles and stone rows were built during this period.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] One of the characteristic types of artefacts of the Early Bronze Age in Ireland is the flat axe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] There are five main types of flat axes: Lough Ravel crannog (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 1600 BC), and a number of metal ingots in the shape of axes.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Bronze Age in Northern Europe spans the 2nd millennium BC, (Unetice culture, Urnfield culture, Tumulus culture, Terramare culture and Lusatian culture) lasting until c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Northern Bronze Age was both a period and a Bronze Age culture in Scandinavian pre-history, c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 1700–500 BC, with sites as far east as Estonia.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Succeeding the Late Neolithic culture, its ethnic and linguistic affinities are unknown in the absence of written sources.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It was followed by the Pre-Roman Iron Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Even though Northern European Bronze Age cultures came relatively late, and came into existence via trade, sites present rich and well-preserved objects made of wool, wood and imported Central European bronze and gold.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Many rock carvings depict ships, and the large stone burial monuments known as stone ships suggest that shipping played an important role.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Thousands of rock carvings depict ships, most probably representing sewn plank-built canoes for warfare, fishing, and trade.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] These may have a history as far back as the neolithic period and continue into the Pre-Roman Iron Age, as shown by the Hjortspring boat.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] There are many mounds and rock carving sites from the period.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Numerous artefacts of bronze and gold are found.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] No written language existed in the Nordic countries during the Bronze Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The rock carvings have been dated through comparison with depicted artefacts.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 3300–2600 BC) was a Late Copper Age/Early Bronze Age culture of the Pontic-Caspian steppe associated with early Indo-Europeans.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] It was followed on the steppe by the Catacomb culture (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The closely related Corded Ware culture in the forest-steppe region to the north (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 3000–2350 BC) spread eastwards with the Fatyanovo culture (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 2900–2050 BC), which subsequently developed into the Abashevo culture (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 2200–1850 BC) and the Sintashta culture (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The earliest known chariots have been found in Sintashta burials and there is earlier evidence for chariot use in the Abashevo culture.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Sintashta culture expanded further eastwards into central Asia becoming the Andronovo culture, while the Srubnaya culture (c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] 1900–1200 BC) continued the use of chariots in eastern Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Arsenical bronze artefacts of the Maykop culture in the North Caucasus have been dated to around the 4th millennium BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] This innovation resulted in the circulation of arsenical bronze technology through southern and eastern Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Iron and copper smelting appeared around the same time in most parts of Africa.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] As such, most Classical African civilisations outside Egypt did not experience a distinct Bronze Age.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Evidence for iron smelting appears earlier or at the same time as copper smelting in Nigeria c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] There is a longstanding debate about whether copper and iron metallurgy were independently developed in sub-Saharan Africa or introduced from the outside across the Sahara from North Africa or the Indian Ocean.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Evidence for theories of independent development and outside introduction are scarce and the subject of active scholarly debate.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Scholars have suggested that both the relative dearth of archaeological research in sub-Saharan Africa as well as long-standing prejudices have limited or biased our understanding of pre-historic metallurgy on the continent.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Copper smelting took place in West Africa prior to the appearance of iron smelting in the region.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Evidence for copper smelting furnaces was found near Agadez, Niger that has been dated as early as 2200 BC.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] However, evidence for copper production in this region before 1000 BC is debated.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Evidence of copper mining and smelting has been found at Akjoujt, Mauretania, that suggests small-scale production c.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Moche culture of South America independently discovered and developed bronze smelting.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Bronze technology was developed further by the Inca and used for utilitarian objects and sculpture.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] A later appearance of limited bronze smelting in western Mexico suggests either contact of that region with Andean civilisations or separate discovery of the technology.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The Calchaquí people of northwestern Argentina had bronze technology.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Trade and industry played a major role in the development of Bronze Age civilisations.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] With artefacts of the Indus Valley Civilisation found in ancient Mesopotamia and Egypt, it is clear that these civilisations were not only in touch with one another, but also trading.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Early long-distance trade was limited almost exclusively to luxury goods like spices, textiles, and precious metals.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] Not only did this make cities with ample amounts of these products rich, but it also led to an intermingling of cultures for the first time in history.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The first and most extensive trade routes were along rivers such as the Nile, the Tigris, and the Euphrates, which led to the growth of cities on the banks of these rivers.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] The later domestication of camels also helped encourage trade routes overland, linking the Indus Valley with the Mediterranean.
[src:château-des-baux/bronze-age-p02] This further led to towns appearing where there was an inn or port where caravan routes ended.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A **castle** is a type of fortified structure built during the Middle Ages predominantly by the nobility or royalty and by military orders.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Scholars usually consider a *castle* to be the private fortified residence of a lord or noble.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This is distinct from a mansion, palace, and villa, whose main purpose was exclusively for *pleasance* and are not primarily fortresses but may be fortified.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Use of the term has varied over time and, sometimes, has also been applied to structures such as hill forts and 19th- and 20th-century homes built to resemble castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Over the Middle Ages, when genuine castles were built, they took on a great many forms with many different features, although some, such as curtain walls, arrowslits, and portcullises, were commonplace.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] European-style castles originated in the 9th and 10th centuries after the fall of the Carolingian Empire, which resulted in its territory being divided among individual lords and princes.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These nobles built castles to control the area immediately surrounding them and they were both offensive and defensive structures: they provided a base from which raids could be launched as well as offering protection from enemies.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although their military origins are often emphasised in castle studies, the structures also served as centres of administration and symbols of power.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Urban castles were used to control the local populace and important travel routes, and rural castles were often situated near features that were integral to life in the community, such as mills, fertile land, or a water source.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Many northern European castles were originally built from earth and timber but had their defences replaced later by stone.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Early castles often exploited natural defences, lacking features such as towers and arrowslits and relying on a central keep.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In the late 12th and early 13th centuries, a scientific approach to castle defence emerged.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This led to the proliferation of towers, with an emphasis on flanking fire.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Many new castles were polygonal or relied on concentric defence – several stages of defence within each other that could all function at the same time to maximise the castle's firepower.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These changes in defence have been attributed to a mixture of castle technology from the Crusades, such as concentric fortification, and inspiration from earlier defences, such as Roman forts.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Not all the elements of castle architecture were military in nature, so that devices such as moats evolved from their original purpose of defence into symbols of power.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Some grand castles had long winding approaches intended to impress and dominate their landscape.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although gunpowder was introduced to Europe in the 14th century, it did not significantly affect castle building until the 15th century, when artillery became powerful enough to break through stone walls.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While castles continued to be built well into the 16th century, new techniques to deal with improved cannon fire made them uncomfortable and undesirable places to live.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] As a result, true castles went into a decline and were replaced by artillery star forts with no role in civil administration, and château or country houses that were indefensible.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] From the 18th century onwards, there was a renewed interest in castles with the construction of mock castles, part of a revival of Gothic architecture, but they had no military purpose.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The word *castle* is derived from the Latin word *castellum*, which is a diminutive of the word *castrum*, meaning "fortified place".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The Old English *castel*, Occitan *castel* or *chastel*, French *château*, Spanish *castillo*, Portuguese *castelo*, Italian *castello*, and a number of words in other languages also derive from *castellum*.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The word *castle* was introduced into English shortly before the Norman Conquest of 1066 to denote this type of building, which was then new to England.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In its simplest terms, the definition of a castle accepted amongst academics is "a private fortified residence".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This contrasts with earlier fortifications, such as the burhs of the Anglo-Saxons and the walled cities such as Constantinople and Antioch in the Middle East; castles were not communal defences but were built and owned by the local feudal lords, either for themselves or for their monarch.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Feudalism was the link between a lord and his vassal where, in return for military service and the expectation of loyalty, the lord would grant the vassal land.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In the late 20th century, there was a trend to refine the definition of a castle by including the criterion of feudal ownership, thus tying castles to the medieval period; however, this does not necessarily reflect the terminology used in the medieval period.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] During the First Crusade (1096–1099), the Frankish armies encountered walled settlements and forts that they indiscriminately referred to as castles, but which would not be considered as such under the modern definition.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Castles served a range of purposes, the most important of which were military, administrative, and domestic.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] As well as defensive structures, castles were also offensive tools which could be used as a base of operations in enemy territory.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Castles were established by Norman invaders of England for both defensive purposes and to pacify the country's inhabitants.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] As William the Conqueror advanced through England, he fortified key positions to secure the land he had taken.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Between 1066 and 1087, he established 36 castles such as Warwick Castle, which he used to guard against rebellion in the English Midlands.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Towards the end of the Middle Ages, castles tended to lose their military significance due to the advent of powerful cannons and permanent artillery fortifications; as a result, castles became more important as residences and statements of power.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A castle could act as a stronghold and prison but was also a place where a knight or lord could entertain his peers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Over time the aesthetics of the design became more important, as the castle's appearance and size began to reflect the prestige and power of its occupant.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Comfortable homes were often fashioned within their fortified walls.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although castles still provided protection from low levels of violence in later periods, eventually they were succeeded by country houses as high-status residences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In scholarship the castle, as defined above, is generally accepted as a coherent concept, originating in Europe and later spreading to parts of the Middle East, where they were introduced by European Crusaders.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This coherent group shared a common origin, dealt with a particular mode of warfare, and exchanged influences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In different areas of the world, analogous structures shared features of fortification and other defining characteristics associated with the concept of a castle, though they originated in different periods and circumstances and experienced differing evolutions and influences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] For example, *shiro* in Japan, described as castles by historian Stephen Turnbull, underwent "a completely different developmental history, were built in a completely different way and were designed to withstand attacks of a completely different nature".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While European castles built from the late 12th and early 13th century onwards were generally stone, *shiro* were predominantly timber buildings into the 16th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] By the 16th century, when Japanese and European cultures met, fortification in Europe had moved beyond castles and relied on innovations such as the Italian *trace italienne* and star forts.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A motte was an earthen mound with a flat top.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It was often artificial, although sometimes it incorporated a pre-existing feature of the landscape.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The excavation of earth to make the mound left a ditch around the motte, called a moat (which could be either wet or dry).
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although the motte is commonly associated with the bailey to form a motte-and-bailey castle, this was not always the case and there are instances where a motte existed on its own.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] "Motte" refers to the mound alone, but it was often surmounted by a fortified structure, such as a keep, and the flat top would be surrounded by a palisade.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It was common for the motte to be reached over a flying bridge (a bridge over the ditch from the counterscarp of the ditch to the edge of the top of the mound), as shown in the Bayeux Tapestry's depiction of Château de Dinan.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Sometimes a motte covered an older castle or hall, whose rooms became underground storage areas and prisons beneath a new keep.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A bailey, also called a ward, was a fortified enclosure.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It was a common feature of castles, and most had at least one.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The keep on top of the motte was the domicile of the lord in charge of the castle and a bastion of last defence, while the bailey was the home of the rest of the lord's household and gave them protection.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The barracks for the garrison, stables, workshops, and storage facilities were often found in the bailey.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Water was supplied by a well or cistern.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Over time the focus of high status accommodation shifted from the keep to the bailey; this resulted in the creation of another bailey that separated the high status buildings – such as the lord's chambers and the chapel – from the everyday structures such as the workshops and barracks.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] From the late 12th century there was a trend for knights to move out of the small houses they had previously occupied within the bailey to live in fortified houses in the countryside.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although often associated with the motte-and-bailey type of castle, baileys could also be found as independent defensive structures.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These simple fortifications were called ringworks.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The enceinte was the castle's main defensive enclosure, and the terms "bailey" and "enceinte" are linked.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A castle could have several baileys but only one enceinte.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Castles with no keep, which relied on their outer defences for protection, are sometimes called enceinte castles; these were the earliest form of castles, before the keep was introduced in the 10th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A keep was a great tower or other building that served as the main living quarters of the castle and usually the most strongly defended point of a castle before the introduction of concentric defence.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] "Keep" was not a term used in the medieval period – the term was applied from the 16th century onwards – instead "donjon" was used to refer to great towers, or *turris* in Latin.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In motte-and-bailey castles, the keep was on top of the motte.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] "Dungeon" is a corrupted form of "donjon" and means a dark, unwelcoming prison.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although often the strongest part of a castle and a last place of refuge if the outer defences fell, the keep was not left empty in case of attack but was used as a residence by the lord who owned the castle, or his guests or representatives.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Gradually, the two functions merged into the same building, and the highest residential storeys had large windows; as a result for many structures, it is difficult to find an appropriate term.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The massive internal spaces seen in many surviving donjons can be misleading; they would have been divided into several rooms by light partitions, as in a modern office building.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Even in some large castles the great hall was separated only by a partition from the lord's chamber, his bedroom and to some extent his office.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Curtain walls were defensive walls enclosing a bailey.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] They had to be high enough to make scaling the walls with ladders difficult and thick enough to withstand bombardment from siege engines which, from the 15th century onwards, included gunpowder artillery.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A typical wall could be 3 m (10 ft) thick and 12 m (39 ft) tall, although sizes varied greatly between castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] To protect them from undermining, curtain walls were sometimes given a stone skirt around their bases.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Walkways along the tops of the curtain walls allowed defenders to rain projectiles on enemies below, and battlements gave them further protection.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Curtain walls were studded with towers to allow enfilading fire along the wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Arrowslits in the walls did not become common in Europe until the 13th century, for fear that they might compromise the wall's strength.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The entrance was often the weakest part in a circuit of defences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] To overcome this, the gatehouse was developed, allowing those inside the castle to control the flow of traffic.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In earth and timber castles, the gateway was usually the first feature to be rebuilt in stone.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The front of the gateway was a blind spot and to overcome this, projecting towers were added on each side of the gate in a style similar to that developed by the Romans.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The gatehouse contained a series of defences to make a direct assault more difficult than battering down a simple gate.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Typically, there were one or more portcullises – a wooden grille reinforced with metal to block a passage – and arrowslits to allow defenders to harry the enemy.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The passage through the gatehouse was lengthened to increase the amount of time an assailant had to spend under fire in a confined space and unable to retaliate.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It is a popular myth that murder holes – openings in the ceiling of the gateway passage – were used to pour boiling oil or molten lead on attackers; the price of oil and lead and the distance of the gatehouse from fires meant that this was impractical.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This method was, however, a common practice in Middle Eastern and Mediterranean castles and fortifications, where such resources were abundant.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] They were most likely used to drop objects on attackers, or to allow water to be poured on fires to extinguish them.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Provision was made in the upper storey of the gatehouse for accommodation so the gate was never left undefended, although this arrangement later evolved to become more comfortable at the expense of defence.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] During the 13th and 14th centuries the barbican was developed.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This consisted of a rampart, ditch, and possibly a tower, in front of the gatehouse which could be used to further protect the entrance.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The purpose of a barbican was not just to provide another line of defence but also to dictate the only approach to the gate.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A moat is a ditch surrounding a castle – or dividing one part of a castle from another – and could be either dry or filled with water.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It often had a defensive purpose, preventing siege towers from reaching walls, along with making mining harder, but could also be ornamental.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Water moats were found in low-lying areas and were usually crossed by a drawbridge, although these were often replaced by stone bridges.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The site of the 13th-century Caerphilly Castle in Wales covers over 30 acres (12 ha) and the water defences, created by flooding the valley to the south of the castle, are some of the largest in Western Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Battlements were most often found surmounting curtain walls and the tops of gatehouses, and comprised several elements: crenellations, hoardings, machicolations, and loopholes.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Crenellation is the collective name for alternating crenels and merlons: gaps and solid blocks on top of a wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Hoardings were wooden constructs that projected beyond the wall, allowing defenders to shoot at, or drop objects on, attackers at the base of the wall without having to lean perilously over the crenellations, thereby exposing themselves to retaliatory fire.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Machicolations were stone projections on top of a wall with openings that allowed objects to be dropped on an enemy at the base of the wall in a similar fashion to hoardings.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Arrowslits, also commonly called loopholes, were narrow vertical openings in defensive walls which allowed arrows or crossbow bolts to be fired on attackers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The narrow slits were intended to protect the defender by providing a very small target, but the size of the opening could also impede the defender if it was too small.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A smaller horizontal opening could be added to give an archer a better view for aiming.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Sometimes a sally port was included; this could allow the garrison to leave the castle and engage besieging forces.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It was usual for the latrines to empty down the external walls of a castle and into the surrounding ditch.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A postern is a secondary door or gate in a concealed location, usually in a fortification such as a city wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The great hall was a large, decorated room where a lord received his guests.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The hall represented the prestige, authority, and richness of the lord.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Events such as feasts, banquets, social or ceremonial gatherings, meetings of the military council, and judicial trials were held in the great hall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Sometimes the great hall existed as a separate building, in that case, it was called a hall-house.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The earliest fortifications originated in the Fertile Crescent, the Indus Valley, Europe, Egypt, and China where settlements were protected by large walls.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In Northern Europe, hill forts were first developed in the Bronze Age, which then proliferated across Europe in the Iron Age.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Hillforts in Britain typically used earthworks rather than stone as a building material.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Many earthworks survive today, along with evidence of palisades to accompany the ditches.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In central and western Europe, oppida emerged in the 2nd century BC; these were densely inhabited fortified settlements, such as the oppidum of Manching.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Some oppida walls were built on a massive scale, utilising stone, wood, iron and earth in their construction.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The Romans encountered fortified settlements such as hill forts and oppida when expanding their territory into northern Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Their defences were often effective, and were only overcome by the extensive use of siege engines and other siege warfare techniques, such as at the Battle of Alesia.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The Romans' own fortifications (*castra*) varied from simple temporary earthworks thrown up by armies on the move, to elaborate permanent stone constructions, notably the milecastles of Hadrian's Wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Roman forts were generally rectangular with rounded corners – a "playing-card shape".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In the medieval period, castles were influenced by earlier forms of elite architecture, contributing to regional variations.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Importantly, while castles had military aspects, they contained a recognisable household structure within their walls, reflecting the multi-functional use of these buildings.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The subject of the emergence of castles in Europe is a complex matter which has led to considerable debate.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Discussions have typically attributed the rise of the castle to a reaction to attacks by Magyars, Muslims, and Vikings and a need for private defence.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The breakdown of the Carolingian Empire led to the privatisation of government, and local lords assumed responsibility for the economy and justice.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] However, while castles proliferated in the 9th and 10th centuries the link between periods of insecurity and building fortifications is not always straightforward.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Some high concentrations of castles occur in secure places, while some border regions had relatively few castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It is likely that the castle evolved from the practice of fortifying a lordly home.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The greatest threat to a lord's home or hall was fire as it was usually a wooden structure.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] To protect against this, and keep other threats at bay, there were several courses of action available: create encircling earthworks to keep an enemy at a distance; build the hall in stone; or raise it up on an artificial mound, known as a motte, to present an obstacle to attackers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While the concept of ditches, ramparts, and stone walls as defensive measures is ancient, raising a motte is a medieval innovation.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A bank and ditch enclosure was a simple form of defence, and when found without an associated motte is called a ringwork; when the site was in use for a prolonged period, it was sometimes replaced by a more complex structure or enhanced by the addition of a stone curtain wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Building the hall in stone did not necessarily make it immune to fire as it still had windows and a wooden door.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This led to the elevation of windows to the second storey – to make it harder to throw objects in – and to move the entrance from ground level to the second storey.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These features are seen in many surviving castle keeps, which were the more sophisticated version of halls.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Castles were not just defensive sites but also enhanced a lord's control over his lands.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] They allowed the garrison to control the surrounding area, and formed a centre of administration, providing the lord with a place to hold court.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Building a castle sometimes required the permission of the king or other high authority.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In 864 the King of West Francia, Charles the Bald, prohibited the construction of *castella* without his permission and ordered them all to be destroyed.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This is perhaps the earliest reference to castles, though military historian R.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Allen Brown points out that the word *castella* may have applied to any fortification at the time.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In some countries the monarch had little control over lords, or required the construction of new castles to aid in securing the land so was unconcerned about granting permission – as was the case in England in the aftermath of the Norman Conquest and the Holy Land during the Crusades.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Switzerland is an extreme case of there being no state control over who built castles, and as a result there were 4,000 in the country.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] There are very few castles dated with certainty from the mid-9th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Converted into a donjon around 950, Château de Doué-la-Fontaine in France is the oldest standing castle in Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] From 1000 onwards, references to castles in texts such as charters increased greatly.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Historians have interpreted this as evidence of a sudden increase in the number of castles in Europe around this time; this has been supported by archaeological investigation which has dated the construction of castle sites through the examination of ceramics.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The increase in Italy began in the 950s, with numbers of castles increasing by a factor of three to five every 50 years, whereas in other parts of Europe such as France and Spain the growth was slower.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In 950, Provence was home to 12 castles; by 1000, this figure had risen to 30, and by 1030 it was over 100.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although the increase was slower in Spain, the 1020s saw a particular growth in the number of castles in the region, particularly in contested border areas between Christian and Muslim lands.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Despite the common period in which castles rose to prominence in Europe, their form and design varied from region to region.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In the early 11th century, the motte and keep – an artificial mound with a palisade and tower on top – was the most common form of castle in Europe, everywhere except Scandinavia.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While Britain, France, and Italy shared a tradition of timber construction that was continued in castle architecture, Spain more commonly used stone or mud-brick as the main building material.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The Muslim invasion of the Iberian Peninsula in the 8th century introduced a style of building developed in North Africa reliant on *tapial*, pebbles in cement, where timber was in short supply.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although stone construction would later become common elsewhere, from the 11th century onwards it was the primary building material for Christian castles in Spain, while at the same time timber was still the dominant building material in north-west Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Historians have interpreted the widespread presence of castles across Europe in the 11th and 12th centuries as evidence that warfare was common, and usually between local lords.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Castles were introduced into England shortly before the Norman Conquest in 1066.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Before the 12th century castles were as uncommon in Denmark as they had been in England before the Norman Conquest.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The introduction of castles to Denmark was a reaction to attacks from Wendish pirates, and they were usually intended as coastal defences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The motte and bailey remained the dominant form of castle in England, Wales, and Ireland well into the 12th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] At the same time, castle architecture in mainland Europe became more sophisticated.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The donjon was at the centre of this change in castle architecture in the 12th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Central towers proliferated, and typically had a square plan, with walls 3 to 4 m (9.8 to 13.1 ft) thick.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Their decoration emulated Romanesque architecture, and sometimes incorporated double windows similar to those found in church bell towers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Donjons, which were the residence of the lord of the castle, evolved to become more spacious.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The design emphasis of donjons changed to reflect a shift from functional to decorative requirements, imposing a symbol of lordly power upon the landscape.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This sometimes led to compromising defence for the sake of display.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Until the 12th century, stone-built and earth and timber castles were contemporary, but by the late 12th century the number of castles being built went into decline.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This has been partly attributed to the higher cost of stone-built fortifications, and the obsolescence of timber and earthwork sites, which meant it was preferable to build in more durable stone.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although superseded by their stone successors, timber and earthwork castles were by no means useless.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This is evidenced by the continual maintenance of timber castles over long periods, sometimes several centuries; Owain Glyndŵr's 11th-century timber castle at Sycharth was still in use by the start of the 15th century, its structure having been maintained for four centuries.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] At the same time there was a change in castle architecture.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The design of castles was not uniform, but these were features that could be found in a typical castle in the mid-12th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] By the end of the 12th century or the early 13th century, a newly constructed castle could be expected to be polygonal in shape, with towers at the corners to provide enfilading fire for the walls.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The towers would have protruded from the walls and featured arrowslits on each level to allow archers to target anyone nearing or at the curtain wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These later castles did not always have a keep, but this may have been because the more complex design of the castle as a whole drove up costs and the keep was sacrificed to save money.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The larger towers provided space for habitation to make up for the loss of the donjon.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Where keeps did exist, they were no longer square but polygonal or cylindrical.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Gateways were more strongly defended, with the entrance to the castle usually between two half-round towers which were connected by a passage above the gateway – although there was great variety in the styles of gateway and entrances – and one or more portcullis.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A peculiar feature of Muslim castles in the Iberian Peninsula was the use of detached towers, called Albarrana towers, around the perimeter as can be seen at the Alcazaba of Badajoz.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Probably developed in the 12th century, the towers provided flanking fire.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] They were connected to the castle by removable wooden bridges, so if the towers were captured the rest of the castle was not accessible.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] When seeking to explain this change in the complexity and style of castles, antiquarians found their answer in the Crusades.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It seemed that the Crusaders had learned much about fortification from their conflicts with the Saracens and exposure to Byzantine architecture.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] There were legends such as that of Lalys – an architect from Palestine who reputedly went to Wales after the Crusades and greatly enhanced the castles in the south of the country – and it was assumed that great architects such as James of Saint George originated in the East.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In the mid-20th century this view was cast into doubt.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Legends were discredited, and in the case of James of Saint George it was proven that he came from Saint-Georges-d'Espéranche, in France.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] If the innovations in fortification had derived from the East, it would have been expected for their influence to be seen from 1100 onwards, immediately after the Christians were victorious in the First Crusade (1096–1099), rather than nearly 100 years later.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Remains of Roman structures in Western Europe were still standing in many places, some of which had flanking round-towers and entrances between two flanking towers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The castle builders of Western Europe were aware of and influenced by Roman design; late Roman coastal forts on the English "Saxon Shore" were reused and in Spain the wall around the city of Ávila imitated Roman architecture when it was built in 1091.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Historian Smail in *Crusading warfare* argued that the case for the influence of Eastern fortification on the West has been overstated, and that Crusaders of the 12th century in fact learned very little about scientific design from Byzantine and Saracen defences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A well-sited castle that made use of natural defences and had strong ditches and walls had no need for a scientific design.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although there were no scientific elements to its design, it was almost impregnable, and in 1187 Saladin chose to lay siege to the castle and starve out its garrison rather than risk an assault.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Civilian settlements are often found in the immediate proximity of these fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] After the First Crusade, Crusaders who did not return to their homes in Europe helped found the Crusader states of the Principality of Antioch, the County of Edessa, the Kingdom of Jerusalem, and the County of Tripoli.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The castles they founded to secure their acquisitions were designed mostly by Syrian master-masons.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Their design was very similar to that of a Roman fort or Byzantine *tetrapyrgia* which were square in plan and had square towers at each corner that did not project much beyond the curtain wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The keep of these Crusader castles would have had a square plan and generally be undecorated.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While castles were used to hold a site and control movement of armies, in the Holy Land some key strategic positions were left unfortified.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Castle architecture in the East became more complex around the late 12th and early 13th centuries after the stalemate of the Third Crusade (1189–1192).
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Both Christians and Muslims created fortifications, and the character of each was different.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Saphadin, the 13th-century ruler of the Saracens, created structures with large rectangular towers that influenced Muslim architecture and were copied again and again, however they had little influence on Crusader castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In the early 13th century, Crusader castles were mostly built by Military Orders including the Knights Hospitaller, Knights Templar, and Teutonic Knights.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The orders were responsible for the foundation of sites such as Krak des Chevaliers, Margat, and Belvoir.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Design varied not just between orders, but between individual castles, though it was common for those founded in this period to have concentric defences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The concept, which originated in castles such as Krak des Chevaliers, was to remove the reliance on a central strongpoint and to emphasise the defence of the curtain walls.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] There would be multiple rings of defensive walls, one inside the other, with the inner ring rising above the outer so that its field of fire was not completely obscured.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] If assailants made it past the first line of defence they would be caught in the killing ground between the inner and outer walls and have to assault the second wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Concentric castles were widely copied across Europe, for instance when Edward I of England – who had himself been on Crusade – built castles in Wales in the late 13th century, four of the eight he founded had a concentric design.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Not all the features of the Crusader castles from the 13th century were emulated in Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] For instance, it was common in Crusader castles to have the main gate in the side of a tower and for there to be two turns in the passageway, lengthening the time it took for someone to reach the outer enclosure.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] It is rare for this bent entrance to be found in Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] One of the effects of the Livonian Crusade in the Baltic was the introduction of stone and brick fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although there were hundreds of wooden castles in Prussia and Livonia, the use of bricks and mortar was unknown in the region before the Crusaders.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Until the 13th century and start of the 14th centuries, their design was heterogeneous, however this period saw the emergence of a standard plan in the region: a square plan, with four wings around a central courtyard.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The Crusades also led to the introduction of machicolations into Western architecture.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Until the 13th century, the tops of towers had been surrounded by wooden galleries, allowing defenders to drop objects on assailants below.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although machicolations performed the same purpose as the wooden galleries, they were probably an Eastern invention rather than an evolution of the wooden form.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Machicolations were used in the East long before the arrival of the Crusaders, and perhaps as early as the first half of the 8th century in Syria.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The greatest period of castle building in Spain was in the 11th to 13th centuries, and they were most commonly found in the disputed borders between Christian and Muslim lands.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Conflict and interaction between the two groups led to an exchange of architectural ideas, and Spanish Christians adopted the use of detached towers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The Spanish Reconquista, driving the Muslims out of the Iberian Peninsula, was complete in 1492.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although France has been described as "the heartland of medieval architecture", the English were at the forefront of castle architecture in the 12th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] French historian François Gebelin wrote: "The great revival in military architecture was led, as one would naturally expect, by the powerful kings and princes of the time; by the sons of William the Conqueror and their descendants, the Plantagenets, when they became dukes of Normandy.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These were the men who built all the most typical twelfth-century fortified castles remaining today".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Despite this, by the beginning of the 15th century, the rate of castle construction in England and Wales went into decline.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The new castles were generally of a lighter build than earlier structures and presented few innovations, although strong sites were still created such as that of Raglan in Wales.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] At the same time, French castle architecture came to the fore and led the way in the field of medieval fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Across Europe – particularly the Baltic, Germany, and Scotland – castles were built well into the 16th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Artillery powered by gunpowder was introduced to Europe in the 1320s and spread quickly.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Handguns, which were initially unpredictable and inaccurate weapons, were not recorded until the 1380s.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Castles were adapted to allow small artillery pieces – averaging between 19.6 and 22 kg (43 and 49 lb) – to fire from towers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These guns were too heavy for a man to carry and fire, but if he supported the butt end and rested the muzzle on the edge of the gun port he could fire the weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The gun ports developed in this period show a unique feature, that of a horizontal timber across the opening.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A hook on the end of the gun could be latched over the timber so the gunner did not have to take the full recoil of the weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This adaptation is found across Europe, and although the timber rarely survives, there is an intact example at Castle Doornenburg in the Netherlands.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Gunports were keyhole shaped, with a circular hole at the bottom for the weapon and a narrow slit on top to allow the gunner to aim.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This form is very common in castles adapted for guns, found in Egypt, Italy, Scotland, and Spain, and elsewhere in between.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Other types of port, though less common, were horizontal slits – allowing only lateral movement – and large square openings, which allowed greater movement.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The use of guns for defence gave rise to artillery castles, such as that of Château de Ham in France.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Defences against guns were not developed until a later stage.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Ham is an example of the trend for new castles to dispense with earlier features such as machicolations, tall towers, and crenellations.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Bigger guns were developed, and in the 15th century became an alternative to siege engines such as the trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The benefits of large guns over trebuchets – the most effective siege engine of the Middle Ages before the advent of gunpowder – were those of a greater range and power.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In an effort to make them more effective, guns were made ever bigger, although this hampered their ability to reach remote castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] By the 1450s guns were the preferred siege weapon, and their effectiveness was demonstrated by Mehmed II at the Fall of Constantinople.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The response towards more effective cannons was to build thicker walls and to prefer round towers, as the curving sides were more likely to deflect a shot than a flat surface.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While this sufficed for new castles, pre-existing structures had to find a way to cope with being battered by cannon.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] An earthen bank could be piled behind a castle's curtain wall to absorb some of the shock of impact.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Often, castles constructed before the age of gunpowder were incapable of using guns as their wall-walks were too narrow.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A solution to this was to pull down the top of a tower and to fill the lower part with the rubble to provide a surface for the guns to fire from.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Lowering the defences in this way had the effect of making them easier to scale with ladders.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A more popular alternative defence, which avoided damaging the castle, was to establish bulwarks beyond the castle's defences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] These could be built from earth or stone and were used to mount weapons.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Around 1500, the innovation of the angled bastion was developed in Italy.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] With developments such as these, Italy pioneered permanent artillery fortifications, which took over from the defensive role of castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] From this evolved star forts, also known as *trace italienne*.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The elite responsible for castle construction had to choose between the new type that could withstand cannon fire and the earlier, more elaborate style.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The first was ugly and uncomfortable and the latter was less secure, although it did offer greater aesthetic appeal and value as a status symbol.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The second choice proved to be more popular as it became apparent that there was little point in trying to make the site genuinely defensible in the face of cannon.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] For a variety of reasons, not least of which is that many castles have no recorded history, there is no firm number of castles built in the medieval period.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] However, it has been estimated that between 75,000 and 100,000 were built in western Europe; of these around 1,700 were in England and Wales and around 14,000 in German-speaking areas.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Some true castles were built in the Americas by the Spanish and French colonies.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The first stage of Spanish fort construction has been termed the "castle period", which lasted from 1492 until the end of the 16th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Starting with Fortaleza Ozama, "these castles were essentially European medieval castles transposed to America".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Among other defensive structures (including forts and citadels), castles were also built in New France towards the end of the 17th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In Montreal the artillery was not as developed as on the battle-fields of Europe, some of the region's outlying forts were built like the fortified manor houses of France.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Fort Longueuil, built from 1695 to 1698 by a baronial family, has been described as "the most medieval-looking fort built in Canada".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The manor house and stables were within a fortified bailey, with a tall round turret in each corner.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] The "most substantial castle-like fort" near Montréal was Fort Senneville, built in 1692 with square towers connected by thick stone walls, as well as a fortified windmill.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Stone forts such as these served as defensive residences, as well as imposing structures to prevent Iroquois incursions.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Although castle construction faded towards the end of the 16th century, castles did not necessarily all fall out of use.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Some retained a role in local administration and became law courts, while others are still handed down in aristocratic families as hereditary seats.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A particularly famous example of this is Windsor Castle in England which was founded in the 11th century and is home to the monarch of the United Kingdom.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In other cases they still had a role in defence.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Tower houses, which are closely related to castles and include pele towers, were defended towers that were permanent residences built in the 14th to 17th centuries.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Especially common in Ireland and Scotland, they could be up to five storeys high and succeeded common enclosure castles and were built by a greater social range of people.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While unlikely to provide as much protection as a more complex castle, they offered security against raiders and other small threats.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] According to archaeologists Oliver Creighton and Robert Higham, "the great country houses of the seventeenth to twentieth centuries were, in a social sense, the castles of their day".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Though there was a trend for the elite to move from castles into country houses in the 17th century, castles were not completely useless.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] In later conflicts, such as the English Civil War (1641–1651), many castles were refortified, although subsequently slighted to prevent them from being used again.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Some country residences, which were not meant to be fortified, were given a castle appearance to scare away potential invaders such as adding turrets and using small windows.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] An example of this is the 16th century Bubaqra Castle in Bubaqra, Malta, which was modified in the 18th century.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Revival or mock castles became popular as a manifestation of a Romantic interest in the Middle Ages and chivalry, and as part of the broader Gothic Revival in architecture.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Examples of these castles include Chapultepec in Mexico, Neuschwanstein in Germany, and Edwin Lutyens' Castle Drogo (1911–1930) – the last flicker of this movement in the British Isles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] While churches and cathedrals in a Gothic style could faithfully imitate medieval examples, new country houses built in a "castle style" differed internally from their medieval predecessors.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] This was because to be faithful to medieval design would have left the houses cold and dark by contemporary standards.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Artificial ruins, built to resemble remnants of historic edifices, were also a hallmark of the period.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] They were usually built as centre pieces in aristocratic planned landscapes.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Follies were similar, although they differed from artificial ruins in that they were not part of a planned landscape, but rather seemed to have no reason for being built.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] Both drew on elements of castle architecture such as castellation and towers, but served no military purpose and were solely for display.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p01] A toy castle is used as a common children attraction in playing fields and fun parks, such as the castle of the Playmobil FunPark in Ħal Far, Malta.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Once the site of a castle had been selected – whether a strategic position or one intended to dominate the landscape as a mark of power – the building material had to be selected.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] An earth and timber castle was cheaper and easier to erect than one built from stone.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The costs involved in construction are not well-recorded, and most surviving records relate to royal castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] A castle with earthen ramparts, a motte, timber defences and buildings could have been constructed by an unskilled workforce.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The source of man-power was probably from the local lordship, and the tenants would already have the necessary skills of felling trees, digging, and working timber necessary for an earth and timber castle.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Possibly coerced into working for their lord, the construction of an earth and timber castle would not have been a drain on a client's funds.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] In terms of time, it has been estimated that an average sized motte – 5 m (16 ft) high and 15 m (49 ft) wide at the summit – would have taken 50 people about 40 working days.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] An exceptionally expensive motte and bailey was that of Clones in Ireland, built in 1211 for £20.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The high cost, relative to other castles of its type, was because labourers had to be imported.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The cost of building a castle varied according to factors such as their complexity and transport costs for material.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] It is certain that stone castles cost a great deal more than those built from earth and timber.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Even a very small tower, such as Peveril Castle, would have cost around £200.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] In the middle were castles such as Orford, which was built in the late 12th century for £1,400, and at the upper end were those such as Dover, which cost about £7,000 between 1181 and 1191.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Spending on the scale of the vast castles such as Château Gaillard (an estimated £15,000 to £20,000 between 1196 and 1198) was easily supported by The Crown, but for lords of smaller areas, castle building was a very serious and costly undertaking.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] It was usual for a stone castle to take the best part of a decade to finish.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The cost of a large castle built over this time (anywhere from £1,000 to £10,000) would take the income from several manors, severely impacting a lord's finances.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Costs in the late 13th century were of a similar order, with castles such as Beaumaris and Rhuddlan costing £14,500 and £9,000 respectively.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Not only were stone castles expensive to build in the first place, but their maintenance was a constant drain.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] They contained a lot of timber, which was often unseasoned and as a result needed careful upkeep.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] For example, it is documented that in the late 12th century repairs at castles such as Exeter and Gloucester cost between £20 and £50 annually.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Medieval machines and inventions, such as the treadwheel crane, became indispensable during construction, and techniques of building wooden scaffolding were improved upon from Antiquity.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] When building in stone a prominent concern of medieval builders was to have quarries close at hand.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] There are examples of some castles where stone was quarried on site, such as Chinon, Château de Coucy and Château Gaillard.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] When it was built in 992 in France the stone tower at Château de Langeais was 16 metres (52 ft) high, 17.5 metres (57 ft) wide, and 10 metres (33 ft) long with walls averaging 1.5 metres (4 ft 11 in).
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The walls contain 1,200 cubic metres (42,000 cu ft) of stone and have a total surface (both inside and out) of 1,600 square metres (17,000 sq ft).
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The tower is estimated to have taken 83,000 average working days to complete, most of which was unskilled labour.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Many countries had both timber and stone castles, however Denmark had few quarries and as a result most of its castles are earth and timber affairs, or later on built from brick.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Brick-built structures were not necessarily weaker than their stone-built counterparts.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Brick castles are less common in England than stone or earth and timber constructions, and often it was chosen for its aesthetic appeal or because it was fashionable, encouraged by the brick architecture of the Low Countries.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] For example, when Tattershall Castle in England was built between 1430 and 1450, there was plenty of stone available nearby, but the owner, Lord Cromwell, chose to use brick.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] About 700,000 bricks were used to build the castle, which has been described as "the finest piece of medieval brick-work in England".
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Most Spanish castles were built from stone, whereas castles in Eastern Europe were usually of timber construction.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] On its completion in 1406 it was the largest brick castle in the world.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Due to the lord's presence in a castle, it was a centre of administration from where he controlled his lands.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] He relied on the support of those below him, as without the support of his more powerful tenants a lord could expect his power to be undermined.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Successful lords regularly held court with those immediately below them on the social scale, but absentees could expect to find their influence weakened.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Larger lordships could be vast, and it would be impractical for a lord to visit all his properties regularly, so deputies were appointed.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] This especially applied to royalty, who sometimes owned land in different countries.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] To allow the lord to concentrate on his duties regarding administration, he had a household of servants to take care of chores such as providing food.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The household was run by a chamberlain, while a treasurer took care of the estate's written records.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Royal households took essentially the same form as baronial households, although on a much larger scale and the positions were more prestigious.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] An important role of the household servants was the preparation of food; the castle kitchens would have been a busy place when the castle was occupied, called on to provide large meals.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Without the presence of a lord's household, usually because he was staying elsewhere, a castle would have been a quiet place with few residents, focused on maintaining the castle.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] As social centres castles were important places for display.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Builders took the opportunity to draw on symbolism, through the use of motifs, to evoke a sense of chivalry that was aspired to in the Middle Ages amongst the elite.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Later structures of the Romantic revival would draw on elements of castle architecture such as battlements for the same purpose.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Castles have been compared with cathedrals as objects of architectural pride, and some castles incorporated gardens as ornamental features.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The right to crenellate, when granted by a monarch – though it was not always necessary – was important not just as it allowed a lord to defend his property but because crenellations and other accoutrements associated with castles were prestigious through their use by the elite.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Licences to crenellate were also proof of a relationship with or favour from the monarch, who was the one responsible for granting permission.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Courtly love was the eroticisation of love between the nobility.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Emphasis was placed on restraint between lovers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Though sometimes expressed through chivalric events such as tournaments, where knights would fight wearing a token from their lady, it could also be private and conducted in secret.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The legend of Tristan and Iseult is one example of stories of courtly love told in the Middle Ages.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] It was an ideal of love between two people not married to each other, although the man might be married to someone else.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] It was not uncommon or ignoble for a lord to be adulterous – Henry I of England had over 20 bastards for instance – but for a lady to be promiscuous was seen as dishonourable.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The purpose of marriage between the medieval elites was to secure land.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Girls were married in their teens, but boys did not marry until they came of age.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] There is a popular conception that women played a peripheral role in the medieval castle household, and that it was dominated by the lord himself.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] This derives from the image of the castle as a martial institution, but most castles in England, France, Ireland, and Scotland were never involved in conflicts or sieges, so the domestic life is a neglected facet.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The lady was given a dower of her husband's estates – usually about a third – which was hers for life, and her husband would inherit on her death.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] It was her duty to administer them directly, as the lord administered his own land.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Despite generally being excluded from military service, a woman could be in charge of a castle, either on behalf of her husband or if she was widowed.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Because of their influence within the medieval household, women influenced construction and design, sometimes through direct patronage; historian Charles Coulson emphasises the role of women in applying "a refined aristocratic taste" to castles due to their long term residence.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Because of the range of functions they had to fulfil, castles were built in a variety of locations.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Multiple factors were considered when choosing a site, balancing between the need for a defendable position with other considerations such as proximity to resources.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] For instance many castles are located near Roman roads, which remained important transport routes in the Middle Ages, or could lead to the alteration or creation of new road systems in the area.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Where available it was common to exploit pre-existing defences such as building with a Roman fort or the ramparts of an Iron Age hillfort.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] A prominent site that overlooked the surrounding area and offered some natural defences may also have been chosen because its visibility made it a symbol of power.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Urban castles were particularly important in controlling centres of population and production, especially with an invading force, and in the aftermath of the Norman Conquest of England in the 11th century the majority of royal castles were built in or near towns.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The positioning of castles was influenced by the available terrain.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Whereas hill castles such as Marksburg were common in Germany, where 66 per cent of all known medieval were highland area while 34 per cent were on low-lying land, they formed a minority of sites in England.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] As castles were not simply military buildings but centres of administration and symbols of power, they had a significant impact on the surrounding landscape.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Placed by a frequently used road or river, the toll castle ensured that a lord would get his due toll money from merchants.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Rural castles were often associated with mills and field systems due to their role in managing the lord's estate, which gave them greater influence over resources.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Others were adjacent to or in royal forests or deer parks and were important in their upkeep.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Fish ponds were a luxury of the lordly elite, and many were found next to castles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Not only were they practical in that they ensured a water supply and fresh fish, but they were a status symbol as they were expensive to build and maintain.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Although sometimes the construction of a castle led to the destruction of a village, such as at Eaton Socon in England, it was more common for the villages nearby to have grown as a result of the presence of a castle.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Sometimes planned towns or villages were created around a castle.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The benefits of castle building on settlements was not confined to Europe.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] When the 13th-century Safad Castle was founded in Galilee in the Holy Land, the 260 villages benefitted from the inhabitants' newfound ability to move freely.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] When built, a castle could result in the restructuring of the local landscape, with roads moved for the convenience of the lord.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Settlements could also grow naturally around a castle, rather than being planned, due to the benefits of proximity to an economic centre in a rural landscape and the safety given by the defences.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Not all such settlements survived, as once the castle lost its importance – perhaps succeeded by a manor house as the centre of administration – the benefits of living next to a castle vanished and the settlement depopulated.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] During and shortly after the Norman Conquest of England, castles were inserted into important pre-existing towns to control and subdue the populace.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] They were usually located near any existing town defences, such as Roman walls, although this sometimes resulted in the demolition of structures occupying the desired site.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] In Lincoln, 166 houses were destroyed to clear space for the castle, and in York agricultural land was flooded to create a moat for the castle.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] As the military importance of urban castles waned from their early origins, they became more important as centres of administration, and their financial and judicial roles.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] When the Normans invaded Ireland, Scotland, and Wales in the 11th and 12th centuries, settlement in those countries was predominantly non-urban, and the foundation of towns was often linked with the creation of a castle.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The location of castles in relation to high status features, such as fish ponds, was a statement of power and control of resources.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Also often found near a castle, sometimes within its defences, was the parish church.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] This signified a close relationship between feudal lords and the Church, one of the most important institutions of medieval society.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Even elements of castle architecture that have usually been interpreted as military could be used for display.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The water features of Kenilworth Castle in England – comprising a moat and several satellite ponds – forced anyone approaching a water castle entrance to take a very indirect route, walking around the defences before the final approach towards the gateway.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The approach was long and took the viewer around the castle, ensuring they got a good look before entering.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Moreover, the gunports were impractical and unlikely to have been effective.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] As a static structure, castles could often be avoided.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Their immediate area of influence was about 400 metres (1,300 ft) and their weapons had a short range even early in the age of artillery.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] However, leaving an enemy behind would allow them to interfere with communications and make raids.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Garrisons were expensive and as a result often small unless the castle was important.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Cost also meant that in peacetime garrisons were smaller, and small castles were manned by perhaps a couple of watchmen and gate-guards.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Even in war, garrisons were not necessarily large as too many people in a defending force would strain supplies and impair the castle's ability to withstand a long siege.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] In 1403, a force of 37 archers successfully defended Caernarfon Castle against two assaults by Owain Glyndŵr's allies during a long siege, demonstrating that a small force could be effective.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Early on, manning a castle was a feudal duty of vassals to their magnates, and magnates to their kings, however this was later replaced with paid forces.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] A garrison was usually commanded by a constable whose peacetime role would have been looking after the castle in the owner's absence.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Under him would have been knights who by benefit of their military training would have acted as a type of officer class.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Below them were archers and bowmen, whose role was to prevent the enemy reaching the walls as can be seen by the positioning of arrowslits.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] If it was necessary to seize control of a castle an army could either launch an assault or lay siege.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] It was more efficient to starve the garrison out than to assault it, particularly for the most heavily defended sites.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Without relief from an external source, the defenders would eventually submit.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Sieges could last weeks, months, and in rare cases years if the supplies of food and water were plentiful.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] A long siege could slow down the army, allowing help to come or for the enemy to prepare a larger force for later.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] On occasion, siege castles would be built to defend the besiegers from a sudden sally and would have been abandoned after the siege ended one way or another.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] If forced to assault a castle, there were many options available to the attackers.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] For wooden structures, such as early motte-and-baileys, fire was a real threat and attempts would be made to set them alight as can be seen in the Bayeux Tapestry.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Projectile weapons had been used since antiquity and the mangonel and petraria – from Eastern and Roman origins respectively – were the main two that were used into the Middle Ages.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] The trebuchet, which probably evolved from the petraria in the 13th century, was the most effective siege weapon before the development of cannons.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] These weapons were vulnerable to fire from the castle as they had a short range and were large machines.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Conversely, weapons such as trebuchets could be fired from within the castle due to the high trajectory of its projectile, and would be protected from direct fire by the curtain walls.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Ballistas or springalds were siege engines that worked on the same principles as crossbows.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] With their origins in Ancient Greece, tension was used to project a bolt or javelin.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Missiles fired from these engines had a lower trajectory than trebuchets or mangonels and were more accurate.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] They were more commonly used against the garrison rather than the buildings of a castle.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Eventually cannons developed to the point where they were more powerful and had a greater range than the trebuchet, and became the main weapon in siege warfare.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] A mine leading to the wall would be dug and once the target had been reached, the wooden supports preventing the tunnel from collapsing would be burned.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] It would cave in and bring down the structure above.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Building a castle on a rock outcrop or surrounding it with a wide, deep moat helped prevent this.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] A counter-mine could be dug towards the besiegers' tunnel; assuming the two converged, this would result in underground hand-to-hand combat.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Mining was so effective that during the siege of Margat in 1285 when the garrison were informed a sap was being dug they surrendered.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Battering rams were also used, usually in the form of a tree trunk given an iron cap.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] They were used to force open the castle gates, although they were sometimes used against walls with less effect.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] As an alternative to the time-consuming task of creating a breach, an escalade could be attempted to capture the walls with fighting along the walkways behind the battlements.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] In this instance, attackers would be vulnerable to arrow fire.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] A safer option for those assaulting a castle was to use a siege tower, sometimes called a belfry.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] Once ditches around a castle were partially filled in, these wooden, movable towers could be pushed against the curtain wall.
[src:château-des-baux/castle-p02] As well as offering some protection for those inside, a siege tower could overlook the interior of a castle, giving bowmen an advantageous position from which to unleash missiles.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] The **Château des Baux** is a ruined fortified castle built during the 10th century, located in Les Baux-de-Provence, Bouches-du-Rhône, southern France.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] Although already inhabited in the Bronze Age, Les Baux-de-Provence did not really start growing until the medieval period.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] Built in the 10th century, the fortress and the small town it protects were ruled by the lords of Baux for five hundred years, in the thick of the ceaseless conflicts that ravaged Provence.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] It was also at Les Baux that the most famous minstrels and troubadours of the day sang songs of courtly love to the maidens of the House of Les Baux.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] In the 15th century, the lords of Baux were superseded by the barons of the Masons des Comtes de Provence.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] This was a golden age for the Château, before it came under the control of the kings of France.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] From the 16th century on, family feuds and wars of religion brought on the decline of the town until the fortress was pulled down in 1633 on the orders of Louis XIII.
[src:château-des-baux/château-des-baux] Visitors to the Château des Baux can see full-scale replicas of huge siege engines, including a couillard, bricole, ballista, and the biggest trebuchet in Europe, which is launched during demonstrations several times daily between April and September.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] A **trebuchet** (French: *trébuchet*) is a type of catapult that uses a hinged arm with a sling attached to the tip to launch a projectile.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It was a common powerful siege engine until the advent of gunpowder.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The design of a trebuchet allows it to launch projectiles of greater weights and further distances than a traditional catapult.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The first is the *traction trebuchet*, or mangonel, which uses manpower to swing the arm.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It first appeared in China by the 4th century BC.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It spread westward, possibly via the Avars, and was adopted by the Byzantines, Persians, Arabs, and other neighboring peoples by the sixth to seventh centuries AD.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The later, and often larger and more powerful, **counterweight trebuchet**, also known as the **counterpoise trebuchet**, uses a counterweight to swing the arm.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It appeared in both Christian and Muslim lands around the Mediterranean in the 12th century, and was carried back to China by the Mongols in the 13th century.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The numerous forms of the word that appeared during the 13th century, including *trabocco*, *tribok*, *tribuclietta*, and *trubechetum*, have obscured the origin of the term.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In Arabic the counterweight trebuchet was called *manjaniq maghribi* or *majaniq ifranji*.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In China, the traction trebuchet was called the *pao* while the counterweight trebuchet was called the *húihúi pào* (Muslim trebuchet).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The English word *trebuchet* is first mentioned in the 14th century (13th century in Anglo-Latin) as "medieval stone-throwing engine of war".
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It is borrowed from (Old) French *trebuchet* (now *trébuchet*).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The French word is from the verbal root of *trebucher* (now *trébucher*) : *trebuch-* + diminutive noun suffix *-et*, *trebucher* (10th century) meant "to overthrow, to bring down", then and now "to stumble", maybe earlier "to rock" or "to tilt".
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It is a compound of (Old) French *tre(s)-*, variant form *tra-* (now *tré-* / *tra-*) from Latin *trans* expressing "displacement" in that case + Old French *buc* "trunk of the body, bulk", itself from Old Low Franconian **būk-* "belly" similar to Old High German *buh*, German *Bauch* "belly".
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The earliest appearance of the term "trebuchet" in French dates to the late 12th century and the first attestations of *trebuchet* as a siege weapon are from around the year 1200.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The 1174–1177 edition of *Roman de Renart*, an epic about *Renard the Fox*, describes it as a "trap whose trigger mechanism consists of an assembly of balanced logs" (understood as animal trap by 1375) while the c.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] 1200 edition describes it as a "war engine that throws stones to break down walls".
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The word *trabuchellus* appeared alongside *manganum* and *prederia* in a document in Vicenza on 6 April 1189 (1189-04-06).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] *Trabucha* is found a decade later with *predariae* at the siege of Castelnuovo Bocca d'Adda in an account by Iohannes Codagnellus.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It is unclear, however, whether these referred to counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Codagnellus did not specify a specific type of engine with the term and even implied that they were "fairly light in subsequent references".
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Only in the late 1210s do variations of "trebuchet" in sources, described as increasingly powerful machines or utilizing different components, identify more closely with the counterweight trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Other terms, such as *machina maior/magna*, might have also referred to counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The trebuchet is a compound machine that makes use of the mechanical advantage of a lever to throw a projectile.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] They are typically large constructions, with the length of the beam as much as 15 meters (50 ft), with some purported to be even larger.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] A trebuchet consists primarily of a long beam attached by an axle suspended high above the ground by a stout frame and base, such that the beam can rotate vertically through a wide arc (typically over 180°).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] A sling is attached to one end of the beam to hold the projectile.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The projectile is thrown when the beam is quickly rotated by applying force to the opposite end of the beam.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The mechanical advantage is primarily obtained by having the projectile section of the beam much longer than the opposite section where the force is applied – usually four to six times longer.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The difference between counterweight and traction trebuchets is what force they use.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Counterweight trebuchets use gravity; potential energy is stored by slowly raising an extremely heavy box (typically filled with stones, sand, or lead) attached to the shorter end of the beam (typically on a hinged connection), and releasing it on command.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Traction trebuchets use human power; on command, men pull ropes attached to the shorter end of the trebuchet beam.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The difficulties of coordinating the pull of many men together repeatedly and predictably makes counterweight trebuchets preferable for the larger machines, though they are more complicated to engineer.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The trebuchet had further modifications to allow an increase to its range, by creating a slot for the sling and projectile to sit underneath the trebuchet, enabling the sling to be lengthened and thus extending the range, an alteration in the trajectory, or the release point to be changed.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Further increasing their complexity is that either winches or treadwheels, aided by block and tackle, are typically required to raise the more massive counterweights.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] So while counterweight trebuchets require significantly fewer men to operate than traction trebuchets, they require significantly more time to reload.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In a long siege, reload time may not be a critical concern.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] When the trebuchet is operated, the force causes rotational acceleration of the beam around the axle (the fulcrum of the lever).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] These factors multiply the acceleration transmitted to the throwing portion of the beam and its attached sling.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The sling starts rotating with the beam, but rotates farther (typically about 360°) and therefore faster, transmitting this increased speed to the projectile.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The length of the sling increases the mechanical advantage, and also changes the trajectory so that, at the time of release from the sling, the projectile is traveling in the desired speed and angle to give it the range to hit the target.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Adjusting the sling's release point is the primary means of fine-tuning the range, as the rest of the trebuchet's actions are difficult to adjust after construction.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The rotation speed of the throwing beam increases smoothly, starting slow but building up quickly.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] After the projectile is released, the arm continues to rotate, allowed to smoothly slow down on its own accord and come to rest at the end of the rotation.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] This is unlike the violent sudden stop inherent in the action of other catapult designs such as the onager, which must absorb most of the launching energy into their own frame, and must be heavily built and reinforced as a result.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] This key difference makes the trebuchet much more durable, allowing for larger and more powerful machines.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] A trebuchet projectile can be almost anything, even debris, rotting carcasses, or incendiaries, but is typically a large stone.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Dense stone, or even metal, specially worked to be round and smooth, gives the best range and predictability.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] When attempting to breach enemy walls, it is important to use materials that will not shatter on impact; projectiles were sometimes brought from distant quarries to get the desired properties.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The traction trebuchet, also referred to as a mangonel in some sources, originated in ancient China.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The first recorded use of traction trebuchets was in ancient China.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] They were used as defensive weapons stationed on walls and sometimes hurled hollowed-out logs filled with burning charcoal to destroy enemy siege works.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] They were used as ship mounted weapons by 573 for attacking enemy fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It seems that during the early 7th century, improvements were made on traction trebuchets, although it is not explicitly stated what.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] According to a stele in Barkul celebrating Tang Taizong's conquest of what is now Ejin Banner, the engineer Jiang Xingben made great advancements on trebuchets that were unknown in ancient times.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The traction trebuchet was adopted by various peoples west of China such as the Byzantines, Persians, Arabs, and Avars by the sixth to seventh centuries AD.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Some scholars suggest that the Avars carried the traction trebuchet westward while others claim that the Byzantines already possessed knowledge of the traction trebuchet beforehand.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The traction trebuchet is simpler in design, has a faster rate of fire, increased accuracy, and comparable range and power.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] According to the *Miracles of Saint Demetrius*, probably written around 620 by John, Archbishop of Thessaloniki, the Avaro-Slavs attacked Thessaloniki in 586 with traction trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] When one stone did reach its target, it "demolished the top of the rampart down to the walkway." The Byzantines adopted the traction trebuchet possibly as early as 587, the Persians in the early 7th century, and the Arabs in the second half of the 7th century.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In 652, the Arabs used trebuchets at the siege of Dongola in the Sudan.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Like the Chinese, by 653, the Arabs also had ship mounted traction trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The *Life of Louis the Pious* contains the earliest western European reference to mangonels (traction trebuchets) in its account of the siege of Tortosa (808–809).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In 1173, the Republic of Pisa tried to capture an island castle with traction trebuchet on galleys.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Traction trebuchets were also used in India.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The traction trebuchet was most efficient as an anti-personnel weapon, used in a supportive position alongside archers and slingers.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Most accounts of traction trebuchets describe them as light artillery weapons while actual penetration of defenses was the result of mining or siege towers.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] At the siege of Kamacha in 766, Byzantine defenders used wooden cover to protect themselves from the enemy artillery while inflicting casualties with their own stone throwers.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The Sack of Amorium in 838 saw the use of traction trebuchets to drive away defenders and destroy wooden defenses.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Some exceptionally large and powerful traction trebuchets have been described during the 11th century or later.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In response, the Seljuks constructed another one requiring 400 men to pull and threw stones weighing 20 kg (44 lb).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] According to Matthew of Edessa, this machine weighed 3,400 kg (7,500 lb) and caused a number of casualties to the city's defenders.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Ibn al-Adim describes a traction trebuchet capable of throwing a man in 1089.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] At the siege of Haizhou in 1161, a traction trebuchet was reported to have had a range of 200 paces (over 400 m (1,300 ft)).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] West of China, the traction trebuchet remained the primary siege engine until the 12th century when it was replaced by the counterweight trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In China the traction trebuchet was the primary siege engine until the counterweight trebuchet was introduced during the Mongol conquest of the Song dynasty in the 13th century.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] There is little to no consensus as to where and when the counterweight trebuchet, which has been described as the "most powerful weapon of the Middle Ages", was first developed.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The earliest known description and illustration of a counterweight trebuchet comes from a commentary on the conquests of Saladin by Mardi ibn Ali al-Tarsusi in 1187.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] However cases for the existence of both European and Muslim counterweight trebuchets prior to 1187 have been made.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In 1090, Khalaf ibn Mula'ib threw out a man from the citadel in Salamiya with a machine and in the early 12th century, Muslim siege engines were able to breach crusader fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] David Nicolle argues that these events could have only been possible with the use of counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Although al-Tarsusi provided the first description and illustration of a counterweight trebuchet, the text implies that the engine was not new and had previously been built.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Al-Tarsusi referred to the counterweight trebuchet as the "Persian" trebuchet whereas the "Frankish" trebuchet was a light traction engine.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Later during the 13th century, Muslims used *manjaniq maghribi* (Western trebuchet) and *manjaniq ifranji* (Frankish trebuchet) to refer to counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Chevedden suggests that *manjaniq maghribi* was used to describe hinged counterweight engines in contrast to previous fixed or hanging counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Sometimes counterweight trebuchets are separated into two or three different categories based on how their counterweights are attached.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] These being fixed, hanging, and hinged counterweights.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] A fixed counterweight is an intrinsic part of the swinging arm and its trajectory is circular.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Hanging counterweights hang below the arm and drop vertically.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Hinged counterweights are attached to the arm by a swinging joint.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Some fixed counterweights also had a hinged component.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The type described by al-Tarsusi was a hanging counterweight.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Writing in 1280, Giles of Rome claimed that hinged counterweight trebuchets had a greater range than fixed counterweight types.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Chevedden argues that counterweight trebuchets appeared prior to 1187 in Europe based on what might have been counterweight trebuchets in earlier sources.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The 12th-century Byzantine historian Niketas Choniates may have been referring to a counterweight trebuchet when he described one equipped with a windlass, which is only useful to counterweight machines, at the siege of Zevgminon in 1165.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] However the source for this was written in the 1180s to 1190s and Niketas may have been placing the engine of his own time anachronistically into the past.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] At the siege of Nicaea in 1097 the Byzantine emperor Alexios I Komnenos reportedly invented new pieces of heavy artillery which deviated from the conventional design and made a deep impression on everyone.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Illustrations produced later in 1270 depicted fixed counterweight trebuchets used at the siege.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Possible references to counterweight trebuchets also appear for the second siege of Tyre in 1124, where the crusaders reportedly made use of "great trebuchets".
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] However the sources for this siege, Fulcher of Chartres and William of Tyre, only mention *machinae* and *machinae iaculatoriae* that were later translated as *perrieres* and *mangoniaux* in the *Estoire d'Eracles*.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Chevedden argues that given the references to new and better trebuchets that by the 1120–30s, the counterweight trebuchet was being used in a variety of places by different peoples such as the crusader states, the Normans of Sicily and the Seljuks.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The earliest solid reference to a "trebuchet" in European sources dates to the siege of Castelnuovo Bocca d'Adda in 1199.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] However it is unclear if this referred to counterweight trebuchets since the author did not specify what engine was used and described the machine as fairly light.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] They may have been used in Germany from around 1205.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Only in the late 1210s do references to "trebuchet", describing more powerful engines and different components, more closely align with the features of a counterweight trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Some of these more powerful engines may have just been traction trebuchets, as one was described being pulled by ten thousand.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] At the siege of Toulouse (1217–1218), *trabuquets* were mentioned to have been deployed, but the siege engine depicted at the tomb of Simon de Montfort, who was killed by artillery at the siege, is a traction trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Though soon after, clear evidence of counterweight machines appeared.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] According to the *Song of the Albigensian Crusade*, the defenders "ran to the ropes and wound the trebuchets", and to shoot the machine, they "then released their ropes." They were used in England at least by 1217 and in Iberia shortly after 1218.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] By the 1230s the counterweight trebuchet was a common item in siege warfare.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Despite the lack of clearly definable terms in the late 12th and early 13th centuries, it is likely that both Muslims and Europeans already had working knowledge of the counterweight trebuchet beforehand.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Counterweight trebuchets do not appear with certainty in Chinese historical records until about 1268.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Prior to 1268, the counterweight trebuchet may have been used in 1232 by the Jurchen Jin commander Qiang Shen.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Qiang invented a device called the "Arresting Trebuchet" which only needed a few men to work it, and could hurl great stones more than a hundred paces, further than even the strongest traction trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] However no other details on the machine are given.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Qiang died the following year and no further references to the Arresting Trebuchet appear.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The earliest definite mention of the counterweight trebuchet in China was in 1268, when the Mongols laid siege to Fancheng and Xiangyang.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] After failing to take the twin cities of Fancheng and Xiangyang for several years, collectively known as the siege of Fancheng and Xiangyang, the Mongol army brought in two Persian engineers to build hinged counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Known as the Huihui trebuchet (回回砲, where "huihui" is a loose slang referring to any Muslims), or Xiangyang trebuchet (襄陽砲) because they were first encountered in that battle.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Ismail and Al-aud-Din travelled to South China from Iraq and built trebuchets for the siege.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Chinese and Muslim engineers operated artillery and siege engines for the Mongol armies.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] By 1283, counterweight trebuchets were also used in Southeast Asia by the Chams against the Yuan dynasty.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] While some historians have described the counterweight trebuchet as a type of medieval super weapon, other historians have urged caution in overemphasizing its destructive capability.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] On the side of the counterweight engine as a medieval military revolution, historians such as Sydney Toy, Paul Chevedden, and Hugh Kennedy consider its power to have caused significant changes in medieval warfare.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] This line of thought suggests that rams were abandoned due to the effectiveness of the counterweight trebuchet, which was capable of reducing "any fortress to rubble".
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Accordingly, traditional fortifications became obsolete and had to be improved with new architectural structures to support defensive counterweight trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In southern France during the Albigensian Crusade, sieges were a last resort and negotiations for surrender were common.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In these instances, trebuchets were used to threaten or bombard enemy fortifications and ensure victory.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] On the side of caution, historians such as John France, Christopher Marshall, and Michael Fulton emphasize the still considerable difficulty of reducing fortifications with siege artillery.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Examples of the failure of siege artillery include the lack of evidence that artillery ever threatened the defenses of Kerak Castle between 1170 and 1188.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] As late as the siege of Acre (1291), where the Mamluk Sultanate fielded 72 or 92 trebuchets, including 14 or 15 counterweight trebuchets and the remaining traction types, they were never able to fulfill a breaching role.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The Mamluks entered the city by sapping the northeast corner of the outer wall.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Though stone projectiles of substantial size (~66 kilograms (146 lb)) have been found at Acre, located near the site of the siege and likely used by the Mamluks, surviving walls of a 13th-century Montmusard tower are no more than one meter thick.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] There is no indication that the thickness of fortress walls increased exponentially rather than a modest increase of 0.5–1 m (1 ft 8 in – 3 ft 3 in) between the 12th and 13th century.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The Templar of Tyre described the faster firing traction trebuchets as more dangerous to the defenders than the counterweight ones.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The Song dynasty described countermeasures against counterweight trebuchets that prevented them from damaging towers and houses: "an extraordinary method was invented of neutralising the effects of the enemy's trebuchets.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Ropes of rice straw four inches thick and thirty-four feet long were joined together twenty at a time, draped on to the buildings from top to bottom, and covered with [wet] clay.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The counterweight trebuchet did not completely replace the traction trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Despite its greater range, counterweight trebuchets had to be constructed close to the site of the siege unlike traction trebuchets, which were smaller, lighter, cheaper, and easier to take apart and put back together again where necessary.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Then when you reach your destination, you encircle the city, set them up, and start shooting!" The traction trebuchet continued to serve as an anti-personnel weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Traction trebuchets were to be used for hitting people in undefended areas.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] At the siege of Acre (1291), both traction and counterweight trebuchets were used.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The traction trebuchets provided cover fire while the counterweight trebuchets destroyed the city's fortifications.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The counterweight-trebuchet could also be used for cover fire and as an anti-personnel weapon.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] King James I of Aragon employed this as a defensive tactic in many fortified structures and towns which proved effective.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Trebuchets could cause mass casualties due to the destruction of structures.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] During an assault on Muntcada by King James I, a trebuchet was used to target a tower, destroying the structure and causing the consequential deaths of civilians and livestock.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] But typically the counterweight trebuchet was used against battlements such as parapets, other defensive structures, and the lower section of walls due to its greater accuracy and longer range, which was how it was employed by the Kingdom of Aragon.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] There is some evidence that the counterweight trebuchet could be transported.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Armies employed a magister tormentorum ('master of trebuchets') for the reconstruction of trebuchets after they were deconstructed for transportation to their destination, whether on carts or by ship.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] They could also be equipped with their own wheels, as shown in two 17th- and 18th-century Chinese illustrations, which are also the only Chinese depictions of counterweight trebuchets on land.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Both Liang and Needham note that the illustrations are poorly drawn and confusing, leading to mislabeling.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The counterweight and traction trebuchets were phased out around the mid-15th century in favor of gunpowder weapons.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] With the introduction of gunpowder, the trebuchet began to lose its place as the siege engine of choice to the cannon.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Trebuchets were still used both at the siege of Burgos (1475–1476) and siege of Rhodes (1480).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] One of the last recorded military uses was by Hernán Cortés, at the 1521 siege of the Aztec capital Tenochtitlán.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Accounts of the attack note that its use was motivated by the limited supply of gunpowder.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The attempt was reportedly unsuccessful: the first projectile landed on the trebuchet itself, destroying it.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In China, the last time trebuchets were seriously considered for military purposes was in 1480.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The hand-trebuchet (Greek: χειρομάγγανον, cheiromanganon) was a staff sling mounted on a pole using a lever mechanism to propel projectiles.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Basically a one-man traction trebuchet, it was used by troops of emperor Nikephoros II Phokas around 965 to disrupt enemy formations in the open field.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It was also mentioned in the *Taktika* of general Nikephoros Ouranos (c.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] 1000), and listed in *De obsidione toleranda* (author anonymous) as a form of artillery.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In China, the hand-trebuchet (*shoupao*) was invented by Liu Yongxi and presented to the emperor in 1002.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It was a pole with a pin at its upper end that acted as a fulcrum for the arm.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The pole was used as a shot for fixing in the ground and the user could then throw missiles at the enemy from a static position.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Chevedden, a hybrid trebuchet existed that used both counterweight and human propulsion.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] However no illustrations or descriptions of the device exist from the time when they were supposed to have been used.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The entire argument for the existence of hybrid trebuchets rests on accounts of increasingly more effective siege weapons.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Peter Purton suggests that this was simply because the machines became larger.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The earliest depiction of a hybrid trebuchet is dated to 1462, when trebuchets had already become obsolete due to cannons.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The **couillard** is a smaller version of a counterweight trebuchet with a single frame instead of the usual double "A" frames.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The counterweight is split into two halves to avoid hitting the center frame.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Most trebuchet use in recent centuries has been for recreational or educational, rather than military purposes.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] New machines have been constructed and old ones restored by living history enthusiasts, for historical re-enactments, and use in other historical celebrations.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] As their construction is substantially simpler than modern weapons, trebuchets also serve as the object of engineering challenges.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The methods of trebuchet construction were lost at the beginning of the 16th century.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In 1984, the French engineer Renaud Beffeyte made the first modern reconstruction of a trebuchet, based on documents from 1324.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The largest currently-functioning trebuchet in the world is the 22,000-kilogram (49,000 lb) machine at Warwick Castle, England, constructed in 2005.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Based on historical designs, it stands 18 metres (59 ft) tall and throws missiles typically 36 kg (80 lbs) up to 300 metres (980 ft).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The trebuchet gained significant interest from numerous news sources when in 2015 a burning missile fired from the siege engine struck and damaged a Victorian-era boathouse situated at the River Avon close by, inadvertently demonstrating the weapon's power.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] It is built on the design of a similar trebuchet at Middelaldercentret in Denmark.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] In 1989, Middelaldercentret became the first place in the modern era to have a working trebuchet.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] Trebuchets compete in one of the classifications of machines used to hurl pumpkins at the annual pumpkin chucking contest held in Sussex County, Delaware, U.S.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The record-holder in that contest for trebuchets is the Yankee Siege II from New Hampshire, which at the 2013 WCPC Championship tossed a pumpkin 2835.8 ft (864.35 metres).
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] The 51-foot-tall (16 m), 55,000-pound (25,000 kg) trebuchet flings the standard 8–10-pound (3.6–4.5 kg) pumpkins, specified for all entries in the WCPC competition.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] A large trebuchet was tested in late 2017 in Belfast as part of the set for the television series *Game of Thrones*.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] A large trebuchet based on Edward I's "Warwolf" was constructed for a scene in David Mackenzie's movie *Outlaw King* (2018) about Robert the Bruce, King of Scots.
[src:château-des-baux/couillard] During the film, it hurls an incendiary projectile at Stirling Castle.
